00:00:30.770 --> 00:00:32.050
- I'm John Campbell,

00:00:32.050 --> 00:00:35.070
I'm a philosophy professor
in the department here.

00:00:35.070 --> 00:00:37.530
I'd like to welcome you to this

00:00:37.530 --> 00:00:39.700
wet and rainy Howison lecture,

00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:43.263
thank you for struggling through
the elements to get here.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:49.093
George Holmes Howison was born in 1834.

00:00:50.049 --> 00:00:50.882
When he was 50,

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:55.000
he came from the University
of Washington at St. Louis

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.140
to take the first endowed chair
in philosophy at Berkeley,

00:00:59.140 --> 00:01:02.540
and he built the philosophy department.

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:07.270
He was evidently a charismatic
and much loved individual.

00:01:07.270 --> 00:01:10.310
On his death, his friends and colleagues

00:01:10.310 --> 00:01:14.190
put together a fund that
is funding today's lecture,

00:01:14.190 --> 00:01:17.720
even still, to continue his work

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:22.280
by bringing the most
influential thinkers of the day

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:26.600
out here to the rural
wilderness of California.

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:30.520
And we're particularly
grateful to Philip Kitcher

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:34.110
for having made that long trek here today

00:01:34.110 --> 00:01:36.453
to the rural sublime.

00:01:37.770 --> 00:01:40.790
Philip Kitcher is a John Dewey

00:01:40.790 --> 00:01:44.700
professor of philosophy
at Columbia University.

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:47.100
He did his PhD at Princeton,

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:49.460
having done his undergraduate work

00:01:49.460 --> 00:01:51.683
at Christ's College in Cambridge.

00:01:52.610 --> 00:01:56.740
He began as a philosopher
of mathematics and science,

00:01:56.740 --> 00:02:01.290
but then focused on philosophy of biology,

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:04.550
and then on the role
of biological research

00:02:04.550 --> 00:02:07.610
in society and politics,

00:02:07.610 --> 00:02:10.290
and then on the role, generally,

00:02:10.290 --> 00:02:12.493
of science in a democracy.

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:16.717
He said, following Dewey,

00:02:16.717 --> 00:02:21.707
"I believe in the need for a
reconstruction of philosophy,

00:02:21.707 --> 00:02:23.567
"so that it will not be

00:02:23.567 --> 00:02:26.967
"a sentimental indulgence for the few."

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:30.950
I think it's fair to say
that his more recent,

00:02:30.950 --> 00:02:32.680
I hope it's fair to say,

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:35.570
that his more recent work
has been deeply influenced

00:02:35.570 --> 00:02:37.830
by John Dewey's pragmatism,

00:02:37.830 --> 00:02:40.750
including pragmatism about ethics.

00:02:40.750 --> 00:02:43.160
And coupled with the pragmatism,

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:47.543
a long standing adherence to
a quite radical naturalism.

00:02:49.590 --> 00:02:52.890
He's written a flood
of well-received books,

00:02:52.890 --> 00:02:55.720
the two most recent have been

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:59.960
Life After Faith: The
Case for Secular Humanism,

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:03.133
and The Seasons Alter:

00:03:04.010 --> 00:03:07.703
How to Save Our Planet in Six Acts.

00:03:08.690 --> 00:03:11.673
So not a sentimental
indulgence for the few.

00:03:13.190 --> 00:03:16.590
He's also written on literature and music,

00:03:16.590 --> 00:03:19.399
in particular, on Joyce and Wagner,

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:22.180
and on Thomas Mann and Muller.

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:25.960
So will you please join me
in welcoming Philip Kitcher.

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:28.850
His title today is
progress in the sciences

00:03:28.850 --> 00:03:30.657
and in the arts.

00:03:30.657 --> 00:03:33.824
(audience applauding)

00:03:35.383 --> 00:03:36.283
- Thank you, John.

00:03:40.330 --> 00:03:41.710
Thank you very much, John,

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:45.563
for that extremely kind
and accurate introduction.

00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:50.680
It's a great honor to give
a lecture in this series,

00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:54.470
which has over the past
nearly 100 years, I think,

00:03:54.470 --> 00:03:56.680
drawn to Berkeley,

00:03:56.680 --> 00:04:00.663
to the rural wilderness
of Northern California,

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:05.130
an incredibly distinguished
series of philosophers,

00:04:05.130 --> 00:04:09.900
and I feel slightly
humbled to be part of that.

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:12.170
But it's a great pleasure to be here,

00:04:12.170 --> 00:04:14.193
and thank you very much for inviting me.

00:04:15.110 --> 00:04:17.410
So what I want to talk about today,

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:20.740
and to the philosophy
department tomorrow as well,

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:23.250
is part of a project to save

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:26.450
what I think of as an endangered concept.

00:04:26.450 --> 00:04:28.970
And that's the concept of progress.

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:33.530
Now, many people in the current
world celebrate progress.

00:04:33.530 --> 00:04:35.940
Steven Pinker has recently written a book

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:38.190
about the importance of progress

00:04:38.190 --> 00:04:40.433
of various kinds since the enlightenment.

00:04:41.750 --> 00:04:43.890
But many people are also skeptical.

00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:45.350
John Gray, for example,

00:04:45.350 --> 00:04:47.150
has written a recent book

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:51.430
in which he questions the
possibility of progress.

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:53.910
He urges us to give up on the idea,

00:04:53.910 --> 00:04:57.810
the myth as he thinks of
it, of human progress.

00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:01.500
Now, there are many skeptics
about progress around,

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:04.280
some people who think that
it doesn't make sense,

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:06.900
that it serves merely as a concept

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:10.460
that we use to congratulate
ourselves unwarrantedly.

00:05:11.330 --> 00:05:13.560
I'm a friend of the concept of progress,

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:15.320
but I have to also to admit

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:17.060
that I think that the skeptics

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:20.600
and the warriors are onto something.

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:24.130
I think that the breezy confidence

00:05:24.130 --> 00:05:28.230
that Steven Pinker sometimes
displays is unwarranted,

00:05:28.230 --> 00:05:32.020
and that this concept
deserves a deeper probing.

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:34.640
And I want to do part
of that probing today,

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:38.300
but in a very restricted set of context,

00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:40.990
I want to talk about
progress in two domains,

00:05:40.990 --> 00:05:44.820
in the sciences and in the arts.

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:46.440
And let me begin

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:49.800
by thinking about progress concepts.

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:51.820
Because I think many of the worries

00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:54.580
that people have about progress

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:58.010
come from not thinking
carefully and precisely enough

00:05:58.010 --> 00:06:00.770
about what a progress concept is.

00:06:00.770 --> 00:06:03.040
And I'm going to do
something, graduate students,

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:06.290
this is a throwback to
the dim and distant past,

00:06:06.290 --> 00:06:10.100
when people talked about the
logic of various concepts,

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:13.513
and I want to talk about the
logic of progress concepts.

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:16.640
So when you talk about progress,

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:19.450
you focus on something,

00:06:19.450 --> 00:06:22.340
I'm going to call that thing, a system.

00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:24.960
And you compare two of its states.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:28.080
And you say, a change has occurred between

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:30.140
the former state and the later state,

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:33.000
and that change is a progressive one.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:34.960
And you can do this for
any number of systems,

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:37.030
you could talk about the Catholic Church,

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:39.830
dividing time up according to papacies,

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:41.510
and ask whether the Catholic Church

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:44.330
is making progress under Pope Francis.

00:06:44.330 --> 00:06:46.740
Or you could talk about the
theory of the chemical bond

00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:48.620
and look at it at various stages

00:06:48.620 --> 00:06:51.680
from the 19th century to the present,

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:54.250
and ask whether that
theory has made progress.

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:58.050
Or you could take a child,
or a young musician,

00:06:58.050 --> 00:07:01.613
and ask, is this musician making progress?

00:07:03.750 --> 00:07:06.600
And sometimes, it's useful to introduce

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:08.860
mathematical concepts in doing that,

00:07:08.860 --> 00:07:12.930
that's especially so in
a fourth kind of case.

00:07:12.930 --> 00:07:16.150
Imagine you have a friend
who's in the hospital,

00:07:16.150 --> 00:07:19.530
there's some substance inside

00:07:19.530 --> 00:07:21.640
your friend's body or in the bloodstream

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:22.810
or something like that,

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:25.980
that is different from what it should be,

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:27.560
perhaps it's too high.

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:30.660
And the doctors chart
your friend's progress

00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:33.400
by looking at the ways in which

00:07:33.400 --> 00:07:36.180
the concentration changes over time.

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:39.860
And if you had measurements
for each time point,

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:41.280
you could, as it were,

00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:46.090
talk about continuous,
the continuous changes,

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:49.290
and the intervals in
which progress was made,

00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:51.573
and the intervals in
which it was not made.

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:56.260
So that's the first part of
the logic of progress concepts.

00:07:56.260 --> 00:07:59.210
The second is that your progress concept

00:07:59.210 --> 00:08:01.530
can be more or less ambitious.

00:08:01.530 --> 00:08:05.310
You can set out to compare
any two temporal states

00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:07.310
of the system that you're interested in.

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:11.760
You give me a pair of
years in the history,

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:13.390
let's say of New York City,

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:16.240
and I'll tell you which
one was progressive

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:18.623
with respect to the other one, okay?

00:08:19.510 --> 00:08:23.030
Or you can be much more cautious and say,

00:08:23.030 --> 00:08:26.200
well, I'm actually not really interested

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:29.370
in making all kinds of comparisons,

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:31.740
I just want to make some
kinds of comparisons.

00:08:31.740 --> 00:08:34.150
And I'm particularly interested in

00:08:34.150 --> 00:08:37.360
temporarily adjacent pairs of states.

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:41.010
That's because I often want
to use my progress concept

00:08:41.010 --> 00:08:42.720
in deciding how to go on,

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.680
asking myself, would I make progress

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:47.083
by going in this direction
rather than that?

00:08:47.952 --> 00:08:50.620
And you might then aim for something

00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:53.020
that is locally complete.

00:08:53.020 --> 00:08:56.560
That is you can make comparisons between

00:08:56.560 --> 00:08:59.260
all pairs of temporarily adjacent states.

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:01.680
But even if you couldn't have that,

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:05.230
having some ideas about
which were progressive

00:09:05.230 --> 00:09:07.030
with respect to which others

00:09:07.030 --> 00:09:09.333
would still sometimes be very helpful.

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:13.760
The third part of my
logic of progress concepts

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:14.923
is the most important.

00:09:15.830 --> 00:09:18.560
We tend to think of progress in terms

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:22.510
of narrowing the distance to a fixed goal

00:09:22.510 --> 00:09:24.940
that's set out in advance.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:27.750
So if you go on a family trip,

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:30.100
and you're going to a particular place,

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:32.570
then you measure your progress

00:09:32.570 --> 00:09:35.420
by the diminishing distance

00:09:35.420 --> 00:09:38.233
of yourselves from that place.

00:09:39.550 --> 00:09:42.500
But much progress isn't like that.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:44.390
There's another concept,

00:09:44.390 --> 00:09:47.010
think of it in terms of progress from,

00:09:47.010 --> 00:09:49.083
which I'll call pragmatic progress.

00:09:50.090 --> 00:09:52.320
Pragmatic progress

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:55.340
occurs when you solve
some of the problems,

00:09:55.340 --> 00:09:58.893
or expand some of the limits
of your current practice.

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:02.470
Okay, think about a technology,

00:10:02.470 --> 00:10:07.080
I heartily dislike the
technology of the smartphone.

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:08.823
I don't actually own one.

00:10:10.110 --> 00:10:12.963
I refuse to get drawn into this culture.

00:10:14.050 --> 00:10:17.610
But the smartphone is not

00:10:17.610 --> 00:10:22.610
oriented towards some platonic
ideal of the smartphone,

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:25.380
glimpsed by those who are lucky enough

00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:28.003
to come out into the light
of Silicon Valley, right?

00:10:29.040 --> 00:10:30.580
That's not the way it works.

00:10:30.580 --> 00:10:34.110
People make progress with
respect to smartphone technology

00:10:34.110 --> 00:10:37.020
by focusing on the glitches
and the difficulties

00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:39.710
and the limits of current smartphones,

00:10:39.710 --> 00:10:41.620
and trying to remove those.

00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:44.930
So we get progress from a not progress

00:10:44.930 --> 00:10:48.593
to any long term fixed goal.

00:10:51.930 --> 00:10:55.380
Okay, so I've begun in
this rather pedantic

00:10:55.380 --> 00:11:00.090
and sort of analytic philosophical mode,

00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:02.360
because I want to draw some morals.

00:11:02.360 --> 00:11:03.830
And the first of these

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:06.470
is that when we think
about progress in a domain,

00:11:06.470 --> 00:11:09.060
like the sciences, or like the arts,

00:11:09.060 --> 00:11:11.860
the first question we should ask is,

00:11:11.860 --> 00:11:15.013
how are we defining the
states of these systems?

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:18.570
The second question that we might ask

00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:20.770
is whether we're committed to

00:11:20.770 --> 00:11:23.890
finding a progress concept
that will be so ambitious

00:11:23.890 --> 00:11:28.630
that it will allow us to
compare any pair of states.

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:31.840
And the third is whether
we need to talk about

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:36.453
some long term enduring
goal fixed in advance.

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:40.310
So I'll start with the sciences.

00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:43.610
And think about some popular
decisions that people make

00:11:43.610 --> 00:11:45.943
when they talk about
progress in this realm.

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:49.110
The first of these popular decisions

00:11:49.110 --> 00:11:51.430
is that when people think
about progress in science,

00:11:51.430 --> 00:11:52.530
they say the things like,

00:11:52.530 --> 00:11:54.770
we know more than we used to.

00:11:54.770 --> 00:11:57.250
And that leads them to focus

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:00.360
on a set of propositions that are,

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:01.600
as is sometimes said,

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:05.050
on the books at a
particular moment in time.

00:12:05.050 --> 00:12:08.010
We might think of those as
the corpus of propositions

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:11.723
accepted by the relevant
community at that time.

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:15.530
And then they make a further move

00:12:15.530 --> 00:12:17.480
that progress is teleological,

00:12:17.480 --> 00:12:21.240
they think of the sciences
as advancing towards

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:23.603
some sort of complete truth.

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:27.180
Perhaps it's the complete
truth about nature,

00:12:27.180 --> 00:12:30.730
or perhaps it's the
complete truth in a domain,

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:33.690
as cell biologists might want to know

00:12:33.690 --> 00:12:36.453
the complete truth about cells.

00:12:37.690 --> 00:12:40.340
I want to suggest that both

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:43.243
of these things are problematic.

00:12:44.710 --> 00:12:47.450
First, as has been familiar

00:12:47.450 --> 00:12:50.400
for at least half a century,

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:52.940
there's far more to scientific practice

00:12:52.940 --> 00:12:55.410
than a simple set of propositions.

00:12:55.410 --> 00:12:58.220
The science of a time contains
lots of other things too,

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:01.890
it contains instruments,
techniques, rules of evidence,

00:13:01.890 --> 00:13:05.113
and we can make progress
in all of these respects.

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:08.720
But more fundamentally,

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:12.350
the idea of scientific
progress as teleological

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:15.273
deserves serious scrutiny.

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:19.590
Think about the idea of the
complete truth about nature,

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:21.280
or the complete truth about any

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:23.313
significant aspect of nature.

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:27.520
As a goal for human inquiry,

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:29.863
that seems absurd.

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:34.073
If Paolo Mancosu were here,
I would ask him whether,

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:36.680
the truth, the whole truth about nature

00:13:36.680 --> 00:13:38.590
might even be too big.

00:13:38.590 --> 00:13:40.750
It's not even coherent to think about

00:13:40.750 --> 00:13:42.430
the whole truth about nature.

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:43.630
But even if it is,

00:13:43.630 --> 00:13:47.253
it's not something that we
could ever hope to attain.

00:13:48.980 --> 00:13:53.070
So I think there are serious worries about

00:13:53.070 --> 00:13:56.853
these standard ways of thinking
about scientific progress.

00:13:57.910 --> 00:14:00.723
And I'll illustrate that by
thinking about this room.

00:14:01.820 --> 00:14:04.820
How many truths are there about this room

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:06.523
for the period of this lecture?

00:14:07.360 --> 00:14:09.970
Well, I was originally
trained in mathematics,

00:14:09.970 --> 00:14:12.480
and when I think about this,

00:14:12.480 --> 00:14:15.020
it's pretty easy to generate an answer.

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:16.670
There's some infinite number

00:14:16.670 --> 00:14:19.300
at least as great as the
power of the continuum.

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:20.430
Why is that?

00:14:20.430 --> 00:14:21.770
Because there are continuum

00:14:21.770 --> 00:14:23.870
many spatial points in this room,

00:14:23.870 --> 00:14:26.290
there are continuum many temporal points

00:14:26.290 --> 00:14:29.800
in the interval that
this lecture will last.

00:14:29.800 --> 00:14:33.920
And at each of those space time points,

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:35.270
there's going to be

00:14:35.270 --> 00:14:38.060
values of particular physical magnitudes,

00:14:38.060 --> 00:14:40.420
and then there are all
the two place relations,

00:14:40.420 --> 00:14:41.690
the three place relations,

00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:44.280
the four place relations, and so on.

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:46.580
You can see you get quite
a lot quite quickly.

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:52.433
Could any human language
express all of those truths?

00:14:53.410 --> 00:14:55.923
If so, which language ought to be chosen?

00:14:57.210 --> 00:14:59.300
How many potential languages are there

00:14:59.300 --> 00:15:00.913
for recording these truths?

00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:04.420
And how many of these
truths are worth knowing?

00:15:04.420 --> 00:15:08.153
I hope the answer to the final
question is more than one.

00:15:09.620 --> 00:15:11.163
If not, I'm in trouble.

00:15:12.410 --> 00:15:15.160
Now, the obvious reply
to what I've just said,

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:16.810
is that that's a distortion

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:20.823
of the teleological approach
to scientific progress.

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:28.210
We don't want them, this
awful, vast mass of truth,

00:15:28.210 --> 00:15:31.270
what we want is a special kind of truth.

00:15:31.270 --> 00:15:33.410
We want nature's rulebook,

00:15:33.410 --> 00:15:36.890
we want the axioms of
the fundamental theories

00:15:36.890 --> 00:15:39.600
from which we could then derive

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:41.400
all of the other truths about nature.

00:15:41.400 --> 00:15:44.240
Well, in principle, we
could derive all of them,

00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:46.300
in practice, we could derive any of them

00:15:46.300 --> 00:15:48.330
that are of interest to us.

00:15:48.330 --> 00:15:50.470
So that's what we want.

00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:51.740
And once we have that,

00:15:51.740 --> 00:15:54.770
we can address any
question that concerns us.

00:15:54.770 --> 00:15:57.340
This image of science remains

00:15:57.340 --> 00:16:01.660
extremely popular among journalists,

00:16:01.660 --> 00:16:03.680
among academics generally,

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:07.920
and among philosophers outside
of philosophy of science.

00:16:07.920 --> 00:16:10.270
They think in terms of
a Newtonian picture,

00:16:10.270 --> 00:16:13.940
the kind of thing that Newton
celebrated in the Principia,

00:16:13.940 --> 00:16:17.340
where he says, I wish we
could derive all the phenomena

00:16:17.340 --> 00:16:19.073
by ways similar to the

00:16:19.073 --> 00:16:23.283
principles I've shown in
the theory of gravitation.

00:16:24.260 --> 00:16:26.810
And scientists in various domains

00:16:26.810 --> 00:16:28.733
have struggled to live up to that.

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:32.720
But it really doesn't work.

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:34.780
And it fails for two reasons.

00:16:34.780 --> 00:16:36.853
First of all, there's vertical failure.

00:16:37.810 --> 00:16:39.470
If you think of the sciences

00:16:39.470 --> 00:16:43.340
as ordered in some kind
of vertical hierarchy,

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:46.050
physics could either be at
the top as the highest science

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:48.480
or at the bottom as the
most fundamental science,

00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:50.750
then there's chemistry,
then there's biology,

00:16:50.750 --> 00:16:53.400
then there's neuroscience
and there's psychology,

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:55.870
then there are things like
economics and sociology,

00:16:55.870 --> 00:16:57.163
and so on and so forth.

00:16:58.030 --> 00:16:59.810
The trouble is that you can't get

00:16:59.810 --> 00:17:02.880
from the most fundamental
level all the way up,

00:17:02.880 --> 00:17:05.430
because there are junctures

00:17:05.430 --> 00:17:08.500
at which the derivations go astray.

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:13.500
You can't derive all the
allegedly special sciences

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:15.910
from the allegedly fundamental ones.

00:17:15.910 --> 00:17:20.350
You can't, for example, get
genetics out of biochemistry.

00:17:20.350 --> 00:17:23.030
But that's less important
than another point.

00:17:23.030 --> 00:17:25.660
And that is what I'll
call horizontal failure,

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:27.920
to distinguish it from
the vertical failure.

00:17:27.920 --> 00:17:31.690
And that is that universal
principles are rare.

00:17:31.690 --> 00:17:33.800
They're welcome when we can find them,

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:36.150
but most of the time in most fields,

00:17:36.150 --> 00:17:39.890
scientists have to settle for
a loose collection of models.

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:41.870
Models that will cover the cases

00:17:41.870 --> 00:17:44.410
that are of most interest to them.

00:17:44.410 --> 00:17:47.340
And sometimes no single model will do.

00:17:47.340 --> 00:17:50.590
I suspect that in climate forecasting,

00:17:50.590 --> 00:17:52.680
we are forever committed

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:54.930
to using a family of models

00:17:54.930 --> 00:17:57.280
that will partially
agree with one another,

00:17:57.280 --> 00:18:00.390
and will partially
diverge from one another.

00:18:02.570 --> 00:18:03.900
The moral of my story

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:07.390
is that science then is
inevitably selective.

00:18:07.390 --> 00:18:09.950
Scientists proceed by looking at

00:18:09.950 --> 00:18:13.240
certain kinds of questions about nature.

00:18:13.240 --> 00:18:18.240
And that agenda of questions
evolves over historical time.

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:21.490
And we might ask how it's determined.

00:18:21.490 --> 00:18:23.570
Most of the time when we
think about a science,

00:18:23.570 --> 00:18:26.110
we take it for granted that the scientists

00:18:26.110 --> 00:18:29.100
are asking the right kinds of questions.

00:18:29.100 --> 00:18:30.580
They are asking questions

00:18:30.580 --> 00:18:32.570
about the genuinely significant things,

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:34.960
the things that we ought
to be asking about.

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:37.970
And almost all the time, I want to say,

00:18:37.970 --> 00:18:41.113
that assumption is completely justified.

00:18:42.250 --> 00:18:44.400
But it isn't always justified.

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:47.560
And looking at cases in
which it isn't justified,

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:49.950
points us in the direction of seeing

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:52.150
how there's something more fundamental

00:18:52.150 --> 00:18:56.520
about scientific progress
than simply taking for granted

00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:59.670
what scientists actually hail

00:18:59.670 --> 00:19:02.080
as the questions that are significant

00:19:02.080 --> 00:19:03.393
and important to answer.

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:09.140
So, let's go back to
the early 20th century,

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:11.470
and ask a question about genetics.

00:19:11.470 --> 00:19:13.010
In 1900,

00:19:13.010 --> 00:19:16.910
three scientists
independently rediscovered

00:19:16.910 --> 00:19:19.120
Mendel's laws, or Mendel's rules,

00:19:19.120 --> 00:19:20.720
as they were called at the time.

00:19:22.110 --> 00:19:24.300
In 1925,

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:26.840
lots of things had already happened

00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:29.390
in the development of genetics.

00:19:29.390 --> 00:19:31.040
People had begun to understand

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:33.650
the relation between
genes and chromosomes,

00:19:33.650 --> 00:19:36.490
they had used that to start gene mapping,

00:19:36.490 --> 00:19:38.730
they were able to identify

00:19:38.730 --> 00:19:42.200
all sorts of details of gene expression,

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:45.080
in particular organisms, in particular,

00:19:45.080 --> 00:19:47.833
the fruit fly, Drosophila melanogaster.

00:19:49.780 --> 00:19:52.260
All of that was terrific.

00:19:52.260 --> 00:19:54.050
And inclines us to say, yes,

00:19:54.050 --> 00:19:57.050
genetics was making fantastic progress.

00:19:57.050 --> 00:20:00.640
But it was also doing something different.

00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:01.880
The building you see there,

00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:03.690
the Eugenics Record Office

00:20:03.690 --> 00:20:07.970
is now Cold Spring Harbor
Laboratory on Long Island.

00:20:07.970 --> 00:20:10.680
And in the teens and the 20s,

00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:14.940
it was set up to address

00:20:14.940 --> 00:20:19.130
and come to terms with
socially important questions

00:20:19.130 --> 00:20:21.890
about things like feeble mindedness

00:20:21.890 --> 00:20:24.163
and the decline of the race.

00:20:25.520 --> 00:20:28.300
Much of this, as was pointed out

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:32.270
wonderfully and lucidly by
the late Stephen Jay Gould,

00:20:32.270 --> 00:20:36.720
was profoundly socially destructive,

00:20:36.720 --> 00:20:40.053
and morally, extraordinarily dubious.

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:45.220
And there was a whimsical side to it too.

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:47.850
One of the genes that was sought

00:20:47.850 --> 00:20:51.340
by the people earnestly involved
in this kind of research

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:54.350
was a gene for thalassophilia.

00:20:54.350 --> 00:20:55.810
Those of you with a little Greek

00:20:55.810 --> 00:20:57.740
will know what thalassophilia is,

00:20:57.740 --> 00:21:00.760
it's a condition typically expressed

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:03.900
in males between the ages of 14 and 18,

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:05.853
that leads them to run away to sea.

00:21:06.690 --> 00:21:10.390
Now, that sort of thing we
could take in our stride,

00:21:10.390 --> 00:21:13.520
right, you're locating
genes on chromosomes,

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:16.440
you're mapping genes, you're
doing lots of good stuff.

00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:18.470
Yeah, if scientists do a little bit

00:21:18.470 --> 00:21:21.600
of peculiar whimsy on the
side, that's no big deal.

00:21:21.600 --> 00:21:24.480
But the genes for feeble mindedness,

00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:28.480
all of that attempt to understand

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:32.150
the genetic determinants of
socially consequential behavior

00:21:32.150 --> 00:21:34.460
was profoundly worrying.

00:21:34.460 --> 00:21:38.400
And so it seems to me that
the verdict on genetics

00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:41.400
in the early 20th century has to be mixed.

00:21:41.400 --> 00:21:42.770
And it has to be mixed

00:21:42.770 --> 00:21:45.570
because the frame with
which we naturally start,

00:21:45.570 --> 00:21:46.510
the frame of saying, well,

00:21:46.510 --> 00:21:49.060
the scientists were asking
the important questions,

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.080
that assumption is suspect in this case.

00:21:53.080 --> 00:21:54.830
We have to move to a wider frame,

00:21:54.830 --> 00:21:57.130
and we have to ask about the way in which

00:21:57.130 --> 00:22:00.743
the science is actually
embedded in society.

00:22:02.580 --> 00:22:05.370
So I want to say that the
sciences make progress

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:08.793
when they contribute to
the wider human good.

00:22:10.530 --> 00:22:13.820
They supply information
relevant to people's projects,

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:15.960
and that information is made accessible

00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:17.830
to those who need it.

00:22:17.830 --> 00:22:20.200
When scientists are doing that,

00:22:20.200 --> 00:22:22.280
it is right to call

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:26.670
their answering of those
questions as progressive.

00:22:26.670 --> 00:22:30.500
But sometimes, they pose
different kinds of questions,

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:32.050
and if those kinds of questions

00:22:32.050 --> 00:22:34.450
have socially damaging consequences,

00:22:34.450 --> 00:22:37.400
then we should not be so swift to declare

00:22:37.400 --> 00:22:40.830
that the science in
question is making progress.

00:22:40.830 --> 00:22:43.260
Some years ago, I tried to embed this

00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:46.840
in an ideal of well-ordered science,

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:49.230
where I thought of the
common good as determined

00:22:49.230 --> 00:22:51.840
through a process of deliberation

00:22:51.840 --> 00:22:54.020
among representatives of various

00:22:54.020 --> 00:22:55.970
points of view in the population,

00:22:55.970 --> 00:22:58.900
who would try to identify
the questions in a field

00:22:58.900 --> 00:23:01.420
that should be given priority

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:05.270
after they had informed one
another of one another's needs,

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:09.060
and after they were dedicated
to try to meet those needs.

00:23:09.060 --> 00:23:11.740
And then well-ordered
science would also include

00:23:11.740 --> 00:23:14.080
the thought that the
answers to those questions

00:23:14.080 --> 00:23:16.373
flowed out into the general population.

00:23:17.620 --> 00:23:19.070
And that gives me

00:23:19.070 --> 00:23:22.070
a pragmatic sense of scientific progress,

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:24.787
science solves certain kinds of problems,

00:23:24.787 --> 00:23:27.370
and the kinds of problems that it

00:23:27.370 --> 00:23:29.757
should be solving to make progress

00:23:29.757 --> 00:23:32.250
are the problems that

00:23:32.250 --> 00:23:34.883
people need to have answers to.

00:23:36.390 --> 00:23:39.280
And that means that what we have

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:43.170
is a broader sense of scientific progress

00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:45.420
than the one that we started with,

00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:48.603
one that involves certain
kinds of social elements.

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:50.660
All right.

00:23:50.660 --> 00:23:52.963
Now I'm gonna turn to
the case of the arts.

00:23:54.750 --> 00:23:57.330
Here, we make

00:23:57.330 --> 00:24:00.660
a very simple way of thinking about this,

00:24:00.660 --> 00:24:03.910
that dominates our
conversations about the arts.

00:24:03.910 --> 00:24:06.400
We think about the state
of any mode of art,

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:09.230
music, or literature, or painting,

00:24:09.230 --> 00:24:11.790
in any time period is
consisting in the works

00:24:11.790 --> 00:24:14.143
that are produced during that time period.

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:19.970
And sometimes we think of one
period as superior to another.

00:24:19.970 --> 00:24:23.680
Think about English drama
between 1580 and 1620,

00:24:23.680 --> 00:24:28.593
and compare that with English
drama between 1620 and 1660.

00:24:29.750 --> 00:24:32.860
Well, the first period wins, doesn't it?

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:36.530
I mean, the first period,
you have Christopher Marlowe.

00:24:36.530 --> 00:24:41.010
You have John Webster,
John Ford, Ben Johnson,

00:24:41.010 --> 00:24:45.500
George Peele, John
Fletcher, Francis Beaumont,

00:24:45.500 --> 00:24:46.940
to name just a few of the people

00:24:46.940 --> 00:24:49.130
who were around at that time.

00:24:49.130 --> 00:24:51.490
And in the second period,

00:24:51.490 --> 00:24:55.000
you're probably at a loss to name anybody

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.350
whose plays still survive,

00:24:58.350 --> 00:24:59.760
anybody who was active.

00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:04.760
Course I cheated, I chose my
periods extremely carefully.

00:25:05.130 --> 00:25:08.430
And between 1620 and 1660,

00:25:08.430 --> 00:25:10.630
well, the theaters were actually shut down

00:25:10.630 --> 00:25:12.400
for part of that time under Cromwell,

00:25:12.400 --> 00:25:14.780
and that didn't really encourage

00:25:14.780 --> 00:25:16.980
a lot of terrific playwriting.

00:25:16.980 --> 00:25:18.730
So I mean, it's a bit of a cheat,

00:25:18.730 --> 00:25:20.770
on the other hand, you can see the way

00:25:20.770 --> 00:25:23.423
in which this is supposed to work.

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:26.670
So the popular conclusions are,

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:28.830
the arts don't make progress at all,

00:25:28.830 --> 00:25:30.610
but the sciences, by contrast,

00:25:30.610 --> 00:25:32.390
are the parade case of progress.

00:25:32.390 --> 00:25:34.337
Well, we've examined the scientific case,

00:25:34.337 --> 00:25:37.883
and I hope I've shown you
what I think lies behind it.

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:41.363
But it's deeply unfair.

00:25:42.230 --> 00:25:45.110
And the unfairness can be demonstrated

00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:47.520
when we look at the
ways in which we define

00:25:47.520 --> 00:25:50.710
those original states for the two cases.

00:25:50.710 --> 00:25:51.880
In the case of science,

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:55.430
we said that the state
consists of a set of resources,

00:25:55.430 --> 00:25:58.870
propositions and instruments
accepted at that time,

00:25:58.870 --> 00:26:03.010
and available for use by the
people who live at that time.

00:26:03.010 --> 00:26:06.080
And progress consists in the fact that

00:26:06.990 --> 00:26:09.260
those resources accumulate

00:26:09.260 --> 00:26:12.673
and become better adapted
to the needs of the people.

00:26:13.660 --> 00:26:14.900
In the case of the arts,

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:18.130
we defined the state very differently.

00:26:18.130 --> 00:26:22.380
We just looked at the works
produced during a time period.

00:26:22.380 --> 00:26:24.580
And so in the case of music,

00:26:24.580 --> 00:26:27.320
we might say music doesn't make progress.

00:26:27.320 --> 00:26:28.860
Did the music of 2015

00:26:28.860 --> 00:26:31.440
make progress over the music of 1905?

00:26:31.440 --> 00:26:32.590
Get serious,

00:26:32.590 --> 00:26:36.280
nothing composed in 2015
rivals Debussy's La mer,

00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:38.140
or Schoenberg's first String Quartet.

00:26:38.140 --> 00:26:40.027
And then there are some pieces by Webern,

00:26:40.027 --> 00:26:42.750
and I can throw in a bit of Desur too.

00:26:42.750 --> 00:26:45.990
Or if you incline to popular music,

00:26:45.990 --> 00:26:47.500
nothing written in the last decade

00:26:47.500 --> 00:26:49.380
rivals the music of The
Beatles, The Stones,

00:26:49.380 --> 00:26:51.510
The Grateful Dead, all those great people

00:26:51.510 --> 00:26:54.670
of the 60s and early 70s,

00:26:54.670 --> 00:26:56.823
you know, get serious about it, okay?

00:26:58.240 --> 00:27:01.717
So, good, let's apply that same standard

00:27:01.717 --> 00:27:03.970
to physics, for example.

00:27:03.970 --> 00:27:06.520
No physical discovery of 2015,

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:08.610
see, I chose my dates carefully, again,

00:27:08.610 --> 00:27:12.240
rivals what Einstein did in 1905.

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:15.320
Four papers, the one that I've got there

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:17.840
is the famous paper on special relativity,

00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:21.300
but we shouldn't forget the
paper on E equals MC squared,

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:23.300
paper on Brownian motion,

00:27:23.300 --> 00:27:25.833
the black body radiation paper, you know.

00:27:27.417 --> 00:27:30.300
I think any one of those papers dominates

00:27:30.300 --> 00:27:34.360
pretty much what the physics
community produced in 2015.

00:27:34.360 --> 00:27:36.210
So, you know,

00:27:36.210 --> 00:27:38.560
what's sauce for the goose
is sauce for the gander,

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:40.720
if we do it one way in one case,

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:43.593
shouldn't we do it the
same way in the other case?

00:27:44.570 --> 00:27:46.640
But the real point of this, of course,

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:49.090
is to get you started
on thinking differently

00:27:49.090 --> 00:27:51.000
about progress in the arts,

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:54.563
not to suggest that progress
doesn't occur in the sciences.

00:27:56.010 --> 00:27:58.050
The physics available today

00:27:58.050 --> 00:28:01.180
includes what Einstein
contributed in 1905.

00:28:01.180 --> 00:28:03.400
Indeed, practicing physicists

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:07.640
don't have to go back and read
those early Einstein papers.

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:09.800
They're available in smoother

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:12.570
and technically more accessible forms

00:28:12.570 --> 00:28:15.653
in the textbooks from
which the physicists learn.

00:28:17.390 --> 00:28:18.890
And the music available today

00:28:18.890 --> 00:28:22.310
includes what Debussy and
Schoenberg composed in 1905,

00:28:22.310 --> 00:28:25.280
and what The Beatles and The Stones

00:28:25.280 --> 00:28:28.260
and the rest of them
did in the 60s and 70s.

00:28:28.260 --> 00:28:29.580
And so in both cases,

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:32.460
we might say there's progress,
science and the arts,

00:28:32.460 --> 00:28:34.850
and expanding collection of resources

00:28:34.850 --> 00:28:38.283
that help with human lives
and human flourishing.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:44.050
So what I want to say
about both of these cases,

00:28:44.050 --> 00:28:47.170
is that the concepts
of progress that apply

00:28:47.170 --> 00:28:49.340
are local, not global,

00:28:49.340 --> 00:28:51.410
I don't think we can make all comparisons,

00:28:51.410 --> 00:28:54.530
and pragmatic, not teleological.

00:28:54.530 --> 00:28:56.200
And in both cases,

00:28:56.200 --> 00:28:59.190
what we get is an
accumulation of resources

00:28:59.190 --> 00:29:01.433
that help human beings to live better.

00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:06.300
And this also brings to our attention

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:08.670
something that I won't stress today,

00:29:08.670 --> 00:29:10.220
but I think it's an important point,

00:29:10.220 --> 00:29:13.510
that in both instances,

00:29:13.510 --> 00:29:16.470
it's an important part of overall progress

00:29:16.470 --> 00:29:19.970
that there should be
institutions and parts of society

00:29:19.970 --> 00:29:23.970
that make those resources
widely accessible.

00:29:23.970 --> 00:29:27.030
So the ways in which the sciences

00:29:27.030 --> 00:29:30.660
and the arts flow out into the public,

00:29:30.660 --> 00:29:32.900
are also very important.

00:29:32.900 --> 00:29:34.530
And without them,

00:29:34.530 --> 00:29:36.780
we might not be as confident as we are

00:29:36.780 --> 00:29:39.270
in talking about the progress of science

00:29:39.270 --> 00:29:40.913
or the progress of the arts.

00:29:42.760 --> 00:29:44.470
But we shouldn't stop.

00:29:44.470 --> 00:29:47.520
I've only so far scratched the surface

00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:50.130
of both of these domains.

00:29:50.130 --> 00:29:52.930
I want to ask what exactly

00:29:52.930 --> 00:29:56.200
the contributions that these domains make,

00:29:56.200 --> 00:29:59.410
because maybe there are
residual differences

00:29:59.410 --> 00:30:02.420
when we look more closely at
the kinds of contributions

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:05.390
made by the arts and by the sciences.

00:30:05.390 --> 00:30:08.933
So let's talk about the
scientific contributions.

00:30:10.770 --> 00:30:14.530
I usually say when I
talk about this topic,

00:30:14.530 --> 00:30:16.300
you know, if I went out on the street,

00:30:16.300 --> 00:30:18.740
and I asked people on the street,

00:30:18.740 --> 00:30:22.000
what is it that the sciences contribute

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:23.670
that makes us think of them as

00:30:23.670 --> 00:30:27.070
important parts of human progress?

00:30:27.070 --> 00:30:29.980
I usually say, well,
what you typically get

00:30:29.980 --> 00:30:34.710
is stuff about medicine,
agricultural innovations,

00:30:34.710 --> 00:30:36.173
bits of technology.

00:30:37.300 --> 00:30:40.050
I suspect that isn't true in Berkeley.

00:30:40.050 --> 00:30:42.400
I suspect if I went out
on the street in Berkeley,

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:44.090
I might get a different answer,

00:30:44.090 --> 00:30:47.630
I might get what I'm going
to call the official view,

00:30:47.630 --> 00:30:50.050
that what we actually get from science

00:30:50.050 --> 00:30:51.980
is an increased understanding

00:30:51.980 --> 00:30:54.423
of the universe and its operations.

00:30:55.560 --> 00:30:58.940
Ah, it's not all the medicines,

00:30:58.940 --> 00:31:01.660
it's not all the new food stuffs,

00:31:01.660 --> 00:31:03.276
it's not all of that.

00:31:03.276 --> 00:31:05.760
It's not the bits of technology,

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:09.020
it's the human understanding that we get,

00:31:09.020 --> 00:31:10.653
that's what's really crucial.

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:13.860
And this was brought home to me

00:31:13.860 --> 00:31:16.370
when I came back from a
run a couple of years ago.

00:31:16.370 --> 00:31:17.980
And I ran into a friend of mine,

00:31:17.980 --> 00:31:20.417
who's a theoretical physicist who said,

00:31:20.417 --> 00:31:22.215
"You've gotta listen to the radio,

00:31:22.215 --> 00:31:24.097
"gotta listen to the
radio, 10:15 this morning,

00:31:24.097 --> 00:31:27.707
"it's the greatest scientific
announcement of our lifetime."

00:31:29.490 --> 00:31:31.180
He was born in the same year I was,

00:31:31.180 --> 00:31:33.570
so I knew that what he said was false,

00:31:33.570 --> 00:31:36.734
since the greatest scientific
achievement of our lifetime

00:31:36.734 --> 00:31:39.540
was made when we were six,

00:31:39.540 --> 00:31:41.940
when Watson and Crick discovered

00:31:41.940 --> 00:31:44.470
the molecular structure of DNA.

00:31:44.470 --> 00:31:48.120
But I didn't want to
sort of spoil his fun.

00:31:48.120 --> 00:31:49.290
And what he was alluding to

00:31:49.290 --> 00:31:52.290
was the detection of gravitational waves.

00:31:52.290 --> 00:31:53.240
All right.

00:31:53.240 --> 00:31:57.290
That for him, and for his community,

00:31:57.290 --> 00:32:00.600
is what's really important
about scientific progress,

00:32:00.600 --> 00:32:03.003
the increase in understanding.

00:32:05.540 --> 00:32:07.640
Now, when we turn to the arts,

00:32:07.640 --> 00:32:10.683
it seems that these
appear much more nebulous.

00:32:13.390 --> 00:32:15.890
And that might be because

00:32:15.890 --> 00:32:18.640
when people think about the
contributions of the arts,

00:32:18.640 --> 00:32:20.930
they think, they compare them

00:32:20.930 --> 00:32:24.180
to the practical benefits of science.

00:32:24.180 --> 00:32:27.550
So if the everyday view
is the dominant view,

00:32:27.550 --> 00:32:30.477
I think one can understand why people say,

00:32:30.477 --> 00:32:32.980
ah, the arts, they don't
contribute as much,

00:32:32.980 --> 00:32:35.100
they aren't as important

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:38.960
in us accumulating these resources,

00:32:38.960 --> 00:32:40.940
the things that are really important

00:32:40.940 --> 00:32:42.140
are the practical stuff.

00:32:43.940 --> 00:32:47.400
So I wonder whether the popular comparison

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:51.330
actually presupposes what
I call the everyday view,

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:53.440
rather than the official view

00:32:53.440 --> 00:32:56.223
adopted by my friend, the
theoretical physicist.

00:32:58.470 --> 00:33:00.330
I want to answer the question,

00:33:00.330 --> 00:33:02.450
what do the arts contribute,

00:33:02.450 --> 00:33:05.480
in a Deweyan pragmatist style.

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:06.960
I want to think about the arts

00:33:06.960 --> 00:33:09.263
as enriching human experience.

00:33:10.160 --> 00:33:12.490
And I want to think of this

00:33:12.490 --> 00:33:14.590
as having a number of different dimensions

00:33:14.590 --> 00:33:17.290
of which I'll list three today.

00:33:17.290 --> 00:33:22.290
First is the intensity of
aesthetic experience itself.

00:33:22.760 --> 00:33:27.480
Just the fact of engaging
with a work of literature,

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:30.460
or a work of visual art or a film,

00:33:30.460 --> 00:33:32.660
or a performance of dance,

00:33:32.660 --> 00:33:35.523
or with a building, or
with a piece of music,

00:33:36.890 --> 00:33:40.170
brings us to moments where I think we feel

00:33:40.170 --> 00:33:45.150
vitally alive and an intensity that is

00:33:47.120 --> 00:33:50.140
absent quite a lot of
the rest of the time.

00:33:50.140 --> 00:33:52.290
So that I think is an
important part of it.

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:54.110
But this isn't,

00:33:54.110 --> 00:33:58.060
these are not simply
isolated events or episodes,

00:33:58.060 --> 00:34:01.350
these are things which
often it seems to me

00:34:01.350 --> 00:34:04.710
recur in our further experience.

00:34:04.710 --> 00:34:07.820
So that later experiences that we have had

00:34:07.820 --> 00:34:12.370
are transformed by the aesthetic
experiences of the past.

00:34:12.370 --> 00:34:15.900
What, our relation to a particular poem,

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:18.600
our relation to a piece
of music or to a painting

00:34:18.600 --> 00:34:22.303
informs the way that we
have further experiences.

00:34:23.170 --> 00:34:24.790
And they interact with one another

00:34:24.790 --> 00:34:28.173
in ways I will want to
try to sketch later on.

00:34:29.460 --> 00:34:32.450
And that can lead not simply to

00:34:32.450 --> 00:34:35.610
an enrichment of our experience over time,

00:34:35.610 --> 00:34:38.840
but also, I think, to cognitive gains.

00:34:38.840 --> 00:34:42.240
So I'm taking a stand here,

00:34:42.240 --> 00:34:46.170
a Deweyan stand on issues in aesthetics

00:34:46.170 --> 00:34:49.270
that often divide theorists.

00:34:49.270 --> 00:34:52.695
I'm saying, I'm putting in

00:34:52.695 --> 00:34:56.770
my case for pluralism.

00:34:56.770 --> 00:34:58.950
That we should not think about

00:34:58.950 --> 00:35:02.780
all individual works of art as valuable,

00:35:02.780 --> 00:35:05.370
in the same way and for the same reason,

00:35:05.370 --> 00:35:07.530
because they may do differently

00:35:07.530 --> 00:35:10.000
on these different dimensions

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.113
of aesthetic contribution.

00:35:14.330 --> 00:35:18.000
So I think in the case of works of art,

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:21.130
they give us new cognitions,

00:35:21.130 --> 00:35:24.480
but they don't do it by
informing us directly,

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:28.040
by asserting or arguing with us.

00:35:28.040 --> 00:35:31.560
The novels and works of literature

00:35:31.560 --> 00:35:34.893
that argue with us and that are didactic,

00:35:36.286 --> 00:35:39.140
I think in particular of Sartre here,

00:35:39.140 --> 00:35:40.273
rather than Camus,

00:35:41.580 --> 00:35:44.040
seem to me less effective

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:47.663
than the works that show us things.

00:35:48.650 --> 00:35:50.390
But the cognitive contributions

00:35:50.390 --> 00:35:53.780
come from modifying the
ways in which we approach

00:35:53.780 --> 00:35:55.820
other parts of our experience,

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:57.983
they show us new possibilities.

00:35:59.030 --> 00:36:00.890
And I want to say they sometimes

00:36:00.890 --> 00:36:02.690
provide us with new vocabularies,

00:36:02.690 --> 00:36:04.660
they refigure the starting points

00:36:04.660 --> 00:36:06.920
and methods of our discursive reasoning.

00:36:06.920 --> 00:36:09.070
When we think about
cognitive contributions,

00:36:09.070 --> 00:36:11.730
I think we have a tendency to think

00:36:11.730 --> 00:36:14.910
as if they consisted in
providing us premises

00:36:14.910 --> 00:36:17.100
from which we might then draw

00:36:17.100 --> 00:36:18.890
new and different conclusions.

00:36:18.890 --> 00:36:21.570
But I don't think that great works of art

00:36:21.570 --> 00:36:23.260
and literature work that way.

00:36:23.260 --> 00:36:25.710
I think they show us things

00:36:25.710 --> 00:36:30.710
that lead us to conceptual revision.

00:36:30.710 --> 00:36:32.160
And that is not necessarily

00:36:32.160 --> 00:36:34.670
something that occurs in the moment.

00:36:34.670 --> 00:36:37.780
It's something that occurs
through the rebuilding

00:36:37.780 --> 00:36:39.440
of something in our psychology

00:36:39.440 --> 00:36:43.360
that I'm going to call
a synthetic complex.

00:36:43.360 --> 00:36:46.170
So think about the ways in which you react

00:36:46.170 --> 00:36:48.730
when you read a work of fiction or a poem,

00:36:48.730 --> 00:36:50.700
or when you listen to a piece of music,

00:36:50.700 --> 00:36:54.520
or when you look at a picture
that really moves you.

00:36:54.520 --> 00:36:57.130
You pass through a sequence
of psychological states,

00:36:57.130 --> 00:36:59.860
and those are partly shaped
by your antecedent judgments

00:36:59.860 --> 00:37:01.390
and conceptions and emotions,

00:37:01.390 --> 00:37:04.750
and partly the product of your
apprehension of the words,

00:37:04.750 --> 00:37:06.493
the colors and the sounds.

00:37:08.880 --> 00:37:11.410
Out of that process

00:37:12.580 --> 00:37:14.780
comes something different.

00:37:14.780 --> 00:37:19.130
And it's something that unfolds
in your reflection on it,

00:37:19.130 --> 00:37:22.980
and in the interaction between
what has happened to you

00:37:22.980 --> 00:37:25.300
and your further experience,

00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:28.230
that rebuilds the ways in which

00:37:28.230 --> 00:37:32.010
your emotional and cognitive dispositions,

00:37:32.010 --> 00:37:35.340
and your dispositions
to use various concepts,

00:37:35.340 --> 00:37:36.633
fit together.

00:37:37.530 --> 00:37:39.770
And so you get a restructuring

00:37:39.770 --> 00:37:42.940
of a part of your psychological life.

00:37:42.940 --> 00:37:44.560
This happened, I think,

00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:48.920
I mean, I will give two very
simple and obvious cases.

00:37:48.920 --> 00:37:53.660
This happened for some Victorian
readers of Dickens' novels,

00:37:53.660 --> 00:37:55.570
when they read not only

00:37:55.570 --> 00:37:58.250
Dickens' descriptions of
the plight of the poor,

00:37:58.250 --> 00:38:01.800
but also Dickens' vocalizations

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:04.450
of the reactions of the bourgeoisie,

00:38:04.450 --> 00:38:06.410
to the plight of the poor.

00:38:06.410 --> 00:38:10.470
People came to see
themselves in those voices,

00:38:10.470 --> 00:38:13.820
and they didn't like what they saw there.

00:38:13.820 --> 00:38:17.427
And it came famously in
Harriet Beecher Stowe's

00:38:18.860 --> 00:38:20.810
novel Uncle Tom's Cabin,

00:38:20.810 --> 00:38:22.950
in some ways as a work of literature,

00:38:22.950 --> 00:38:25.090
it's not a wonderful piece of writing,

00:38:25.090 --> 00:38:27.489
but boy is it powerful

00:38:27.489 --> 00:38:32.070
in changing the ways in which people think

00:38:32.070 --> 00:38:35.330
about their social relations with others.

00:38:35.330 --> 00:38:37.780
Even if Lincoln didn't say

00:38:37.780 --> 00:38:40.387
to Harriet Beecher Stowe when he met her,

00:38:40.387 --> 00:38:43.360
"So you're the little lady
who started this great war,"

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:46.113
it's something it seems to
me, he ought to have said.

00:38:47.150 --> 00:38:50.130
So I think the same thing goes on

00:38:50.130 --> 00:38:53.240
in our interactions with
bits of science, sometimes.

00:38:53.240 --> 00:38:55.010
I think scientific understanding

00:38:55.010 --> 00:38:57.913
can do the same sort of thing.

00:38:59.160 --> 00:39:01.420
I think it did that for Richard Dawkins,

00:39:01.420 --> 00:39:04.860
who's written eloquently about this,

00:39:04.860 --> 00:39:07.330
and who says, very often,

00:39:07.330 --> 00:39:09.757
you know, "How unfortunate
are those people

00:39:09.757 --> 00:39:12.037
"who are deprived of seeing the world

00:39:12.037 --> 00:39:13.597
"through a Darwinian lens,

00:39:13.597 --> 00:39:15.690
"look at what they are missing."

00:39:15.690 --> 00:39:18.810
And I resonate with that in Dawkins,

00:39:18.810 --> 00:39:20.460
I can see why he says it,

00:39:20.460 --> 00:39:23.150
and I think I can
understand the phenomenon

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:24.733
to which he is pointing.

00:39:26.800 --> 00:39:29.840
But now, I want to ask a question.

00:39:29.840 --> 00:39:32.480
We won't have a vote on this.

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:36.300
But when I've asked questions of people

00:39:36.300 --> 00:39:39.100
I've talked to about this
material in the past,

00:39:39.100 --> 00:39:43.980
I get a fairly strong reaction.

00:39:43.980 --> 00:39:46.380
And that is that most people

00:39:46.380 --> 00:39:48.800
in whom I ask about this,

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:50.087
after they've heard me talk about,

00:39:50.087 --> 00:39:51.750
you know, art and science

00:39:51.750 --> 00:39:54.120
and along these or similar lines,

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:55.940
will say, yeah, actually, for me,

00:39:55.940 --> 00:39:57.680
it's the works of literature I've read,

00:39:57.680 --> 00:40:00.313
it's the music I've heard,
it's the films I've seen.

00:40:01.496 --> 00:40:03.210
That's what's done most for me

00:40:05.410 --> 00:40:08.653
in having an impact for change in my life.

00:40:09.920 --> 00:40:12.660
But many people who are deeply immersed

00:40:12.660 --> 00:40:14.820
in the practice of the sciences will say,

00:40:14.820 --> 00:40:16.990
no, it's the sciences.

00:40:16.990 --> 00:40:21.690
I don't want to make judgments about this,

00:40:21.690 --> 00:40:24.509
I think there are possibly temperaments

00:40:24.509 --> 00:40:29.077
that lead people into different
areas of work and research,

00:40:29.077 --> 00:40:32.400
and some people may, because
of their temperaments,

00:40:32.400 --> 00:40:35.600
be more inclined to pursue courses of life

00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:38.900
that lead the arts to be
more important for them

00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:40.063
than the sciences.

00:40:42.410 --> 00:40:44.010
Another question we might ask

00:40:44.010 --> 00:40:47.280
is whether within the sciences themselves,

00:40:47.280 --> 00:40:51.430
these artistic reshapings
play a critical role

00:40:51.430 --> 00:40:53.840
at moments of great scientific change.

00:40:53.840 --> 00:40:56.230
That's a thesis that Thomas Kuhn,

00:40:56.230 --> 00:40:59.693
who once taught here at Berkeley,

00:41:00.850 --> 00:41:03.100
floated in a book that he wrote

00:41:03.100 --> 00:41:05.210
before the structure of
scientific revolutions,

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:07.283
in his book on the Copernican revolution.

00:41:08.730 --> 00:41:10.610
So I'm going to,

00:41:10.610 --> 00:41:13.890
just a moment of subversion,

00:41:13.890 --> 00:41:15.530
a subversive thesis.

00:41:15.530 --> 00:41:17.840
If scientific progress is understood

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:21.300
in terms of the pure benefits
of greater understanding,

00:41:21.300 --> 00:41:23.750
maybe the case for progress in the arts

00:41:23.750 --> 00:41:27.170
is stronger than that, for
progress in the sciences,

00:41:27.170 --> 00:41:29.930
because of the phenomenon
to which I've just alluded.

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:32.650
The fact that it seems
that for most people,

00:41:32.650 --> 00:41:35.120
it's works of art that have this

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:37.913
transformative impact on their lives.

00:41:39.200 --> 00:41:41.340
But there's a residual difference,

00:41:41.340 --> 00:41:43.360
and this is going to lead me back

00:41:43.360 --> 00:41:45.773
towards the worries with which I began.

00:41:47.390 --> 00:41:49.010
Scientific progress, you might say,

00:41:49.010 --> 00:41:52.613
is cumulative in ways that
progress in the arts isn't.

00:41:53.660 --> 00:41:54.703
And that's because of a phenomena

00:41:54.703 --> 00:41:57.210
that I pointed to earlier,

00:41:57.210 --> 00:41:59.360
that the scientists don't have to go back

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:02.830
and read Einstein's 1905 relativity paper.

00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:05.160
The later stages of a science absorb

00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:07.840
and they build on the
efforts of earlier stages,

00:42:07.840 --> 00:42:10.670
whereas the arts, always are looking for

00:42:10.670 --> 00:42:14.053
new ways forward, new forms of creativity.

00:42:15.430 --> 00:42:18.997
In the words of Harold Bloom,

00:42:18.997 --> 00:42:23.160
"Poets engage in strong
misreadings of their predecessors."

00:42:23.160 --> 00:42:25.963
They don't, sort of,

00:42:26.820 --> 00:42:28.620
just thrust them into the past,

00:42:28.620 --> 00:42:32.293
they wrestle with them and
come to something entirely new.

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:36.370
Now in changing environments,

00:42:36.370 --> 00:42:37.890
new directions in art,

00:42:37.890 --> 00:42:40.783
and sometimes new genres
of art are needed.

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:44.770
The works of literature
that might have satisfied

00:42:44.770 --> 00:42:47.620
one particular generation living

00:42:47.620 --> 00:42:51.920
in a particular kind of world don't speak,

00:42:51.920 --> 00:42:54.390
or they don't speak vividly and forcefully

00:42:54.390 --> 00:42:56.093
to people who live later.

00:42:57.260 --> 00:42:59.990
And that's because the
environments in which we live,

00:42:59.990 --> 00:43:02.973
physical, social and cultural can change.

00:43:04.330 --> 00:43:07.210
So art we might think
of as constantly renewed

00:43:07.210 --> 00:43:09.873
to adapt to the features of the age.

00:43:13.860 --> 00:43:16.930
Not all past artworks
lose their significance

00:43:16.930 --> 00:43:19.053
by any means, that's for sure.

00:43:20.330 --> 00:43:22.410
In the history of the string quartet,

00:43:22.410 --> 00:43:24.870
the great string quartets
of the 20th century,

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:27.310
Schoenberg's, Bartok's, Janacek's,

00:43:27.310 --> 00:43:31.423
don't make Beethoven and
Haydn and Mozart irrelevant.

00:43:32.960 --> 00:43:34.600
But by contrast,

00:43:34.600 --> 00:43:38.130
the words and things that
all the scientists produce

00:43:38.130 --> 00:43:39.530
are often hidden

00:43:39.530 --> 00:43:42.493
by the accomplishments
of their successors.

00:43:44.090 --> 00:43:47.550
So nobody would go back
and try to learn chemistry

00:43:47.550 --> 00:43:49.913
from Lavoisier's revolutionary book.

00:43:50.890 --> 00:43:53.540
Nobody interested in astronomy today

00:43:53.540 --> 00:43:56.910
would pick up Galileo's telescope.

00:43:56.910 --> 00:43:58.110
Interestingly though,

00:43:58.110 --> 00:44:01.710
biologists still turn back to Darwin.

00:44:01.710 --> 00:44:05.820
Darwin is one of the
great exceptions to this.

00:44:05.820 --> 00:44:09.573
Darwin continues to be relevant
to the biology of today.

00:44:11.720 --> 00:44:16.170
And in this process, there's a change.

00:44:16.170 --> 00:44:18.020
And I think Eliot caught this

00:44:18.020 --> 00:44:21.480
in his essay on tradition
and the individual talent.

00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:24.307
Where he says, "No poet,
no artist of any art

00:44:24.307 --> 00:44:26.407
"has his complete meaning alone.

00:44:26.407 --> 00:44:28.317
"You cannot value him alone,

00:44:28.317 --> 00:44:29.747
"you must set him for contrast

00:44:29.747 --> 00:44:31.517
"and comparison among the dead.

00:44:31.517 --> 00:44:33.947
"What happens when a new
work of art is created

00:44:33.947 --> 00:44:36.297
"is something that happens simultaneously

00:44:36.297 --> 00:44:39.327
"to all the works of
art which preceded it."

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:43.720
And that means that there are gains

00:44:43.720 --> 00:44:46.340
and losses with respect to the arts.

00:44:46.340 --> 00:44:48.760
And that happened with respect to poetry

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:50.910
because of the kind of poetry

00:44:50.910 --> 00:44:52.970
that Eliot and his friends wrote.

00:44:52.970 --> 00:44:55.230
After Eliot, Pound and Yates,

00:44:55.230 --> 00:44:59.640
Dante, Donne and Tennyson
get read differently.

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:02.640
Dante is somehow elevated,

00:45:02.640 --> 00:45:04.780
he's somehow much more relevant,

00:45:04.780 --> 00:45:07.343
much more important than he had seemed,

00:45:08.320 --> 00:45:10.420
say, to the Victorians.

00:45:10.420 --> 00:45:13.910
Donne emerges from being a quirky

00:45:15.096 --> 00:45:17.810
odd figure in the 17th century,

00:45:17.810 --> 00:45:20.120
to being a lively and interesting

00:45:20.120 --> 00:45:22.700
and profoundly relevant poet.

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:24.023
And poor Tennyson,

00:45:25.524 --> 00:45:29.510
the beloved poet of the mid
19th century and beyond,

00:45:29.510 --> 00:45:34.163
somehow sounds lesser than he did.

00:45:37.070 --> 00:45:40.200
If you listen to Schoenberg's
third string quartet,

00:45:40.200 --> 00:45:43.300
and then listen to Beethoven's
third Rasumovsky quartet,

00:45:43.300 --> 00:45:45.350
as I once did at a concert in Berlin,

00:45:45.350 --> 00:45:47.200
where they played them in that order,

00:45:48.060 --> 00:45:49.160
the Beethoven sounds

00:45:49.160 --> 00:45:51.070
completely different after the Schoenberg,

00:45:51.070 --> 00:45:52.300
and you can understand why

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:55.430
the first performance of
the Rasumovsky quartets,

00:45:55.430 --> 00:45:57.140
the musicians protested,

00:45:57.140 --> 00:46:00.320
tore up the scores and trampled on them.

00:46:00.320 --> 00:46:03.083
I mean, it suddenly sounds
incredibly revolutionary.

00:46:04.730 --> 00:46:08.730
So these things, this point
that derives from Eliot,

00:46:08.730 --> 00:46:11.220
I think, raises a possibility,

00:46:11.220 --> 00:46:13.240
the possibility of loss.

00:46:13.240 --> 00:46:16.470
That you can lose access
to a former work of art

00:46:16.470 --> 00:46:18.463
that might have been valuable for you.

00:46:20.350 --> 00:46:22.530
And I wonder whether the same can happen

00:46:22.530 --> 00:46:24.523
with respect to the sciences.

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:29.040
But the important theme
that I want to draw

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:31.380
from this general phenomenon,

00:46:31.380 --> 00:46:34.280
concerns something that I think is

00:46:34.280 --> 00:46:37.030
deeply lying behind the skepticism

00:46:37.030 --> 00:46:39.860
about progress with which I began.

00:46:39.860 --> 00:46:43.160
And that's the idea of people somehow

00:46:43.160 --> 00:46:46.840
being at odds with their
own times with the age.

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:48.533
You know, I have already confessed,

00:46:48.533 --> 00:46:50.280
I don't own a smartphone,

00:46:50.280 --> 00:46:52.693
so maybe I am one of these people.

00:46:53.970 --> 00:46:56.100
I think it makes sense
to say of some people

00:46:56.100 --> 00:46:58.050
that their lives would have gone better

00:46:58.050 --> 00:47:00.150
if they'd lived in earlier times,

00:47:00.150 --> 00:47:01.910
that their temperaments and talents

00:47:01.910 --> 00:47:04.793
are more adapted to those times.

00:47:07.620 --> 00:47:11.240
And that means that we might think

00:47:11.240 --> 00:47:13.750
that the artistic or scientific resources

00:47:13.750 --> 00:47:15.780
available at a later time,

00:47:15.780 --> 00:47:18.300
do not allow the people living at the time

00:47:18.300 --> 00:47:21.210
to live as well as they would have done

00:47:21.210 --> 00:47:23.270
at some earlier time.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:27.400
They are less well adapted
than they would have been.

00:47:27.400 --> 00:47:30.160
And this means that my comparison

00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:33.610
on which I have been building
throughout this lecture,

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:36.510
is only one possible way

00:47:36.510 --> 00:47:38.340
of making these comparisons.

00:47:38.340 --> 00:47:41.170
There are in fact, two concepts

00:47:42.170 --> 00:47:44.680
that we might focus on in thinking about

00:47:44.680 --> 00:47:47.580
socially embedded notions of progress

00:47:47.580 --> 00:47:49.383
for the arts and the sciences.

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:53.890
The first says, fix the environment.

00:47:53.890 --> 00:47:54.973
Fix the present.

00:47:56.440 --> 00:47:58.490
Ask whether life in this environment

00:47:58.490 --> 00:48:01.090
would go better with the
resources of the past

00:48:01.090 --> 00:48:03.010
or with those of the present.

00:48:03.010 --> 00:48:04.110
That's what I've used,

00:48:04.110 --> 00:48:05.540
and I've said, well,

00:48:05.540 --> 00:48:06.900
in the present, typically,

00:48:06.900 --> 00:48:08.370
you have most of the resources

00:48:08.370 --> 00:48:10.900
that you would have had in the
past and a few more besides,

00:48:10.900 --> 00:48:13.220
and in both cases, probably the things

00:48:13.220 --> 00:48:15.090
that are developed in the sciences

00:48:15.090 --> 00:48:18.072
are adapted to the differences

00:48:18.072 --> 00:48:20.890
that have emerged in the present.

00:48:20.890 --> 00:48:23.533
So progress comes quite easily.

00:48:24.470 --> 00:48:26.083
But ask a different question.

00:48:26.960 --> 00:48:29.540
Consider life with the past resources

00:48:29.540 --> 00:48:31.430
in the past environment,

00:48:31.430 --> 00:48:34.260
compare it with life with
the present resources

00:48:34.260 --> 00:48:35.923
in the present environment.

00:48:36.860 --> 00:48:39.450
If you do that, you may
not get the same answer,

00:48:39.450 --> 00:48:41.363
you might get different verdicts.

00:48:42.650 --> 00:48:46.163
So there are two notions or
two standards for progress.

00:48:47.440 --> 00:48:50.140
I want to say that a practice like science

00:48:50.140 --> 00:48:53.140
or art or religion
would make weak progress

00:48:53.140 --> 00:48:55.730
if the developments
between the earlier stage

00:48:55.730 --> 00:48:57.740
and the later stage enable those

00:48:57.740 --> 00:49:00.070
who live at the later stage to live better

00:49:00.070 --> 00:49:00.980
than they would have done

00:49:00.980 --> 00:49:04.680
if the earlier form of the
practice had continued unaltered.

00:49:04.680 --> 00:49:07.080
That's the notion where
you fix the environment.

00:49:10.440 --> 00:49:12.910
It makes strong progress

00:49:12.910 --> 00:49:14.670
if the developments made between

00:49:14.670 --> 00:49:16.700
the earlier stage and the later stage

00:49:16.700 --> 00:49:19.110
enable those who live at the later stage

00:49:19.110 --> 00:49:23.273
to live better than those who
lived at the earlier stage.

00:49:24.220 --> 00:49:27.980
The people who are
skeptical about progress

00:49:27.980 --> 00:49:31.963
are skeptical often about strong progress.

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:36.680
And I haven't really responded
to what they say here.

00:49:36.680 --> 00:49:40.723
That's because I think
that they have a point.

00:49:42.120 --> 00:49:45.800
So I'll conclude, I think
weak progress is very common

00:49:45.800 --> 00:49:48.910
in the histories of both
the sciences and the arts.

00:49:48.910 --> 00:49:50.970
I think strong progress often occurs

00:49:50.970 --> 00:49:53.090
in the histories of the
sciences and the arts.

00:49:53.090 --> 00:49:54.320
But in both cases,

00:49:54.320 --> 00:49:56.290
there may be significant periods

00:49:56.290 --> 00:49:58.713
during which strong progress is not made.

00:50:01.220 --> 00:50:03.330
And worries about strong progress

00:50:03.330 --> 00:50:06.517
underlie the common forms of
skepticism about progress,

00:50:06.517 --> 00:50:09.363
and those need to be
addressed and dealt with.

00:50:10.870 --> 00:50:13.010
Now, how does it come about

00:50:13.010 --> 00:50:15.430
that strong progress fails

00:50:15.430 --> 00:50:17.870
where weak progress happens?

00:50:17.870 --> 00:50:21.203
The answer lies in a point
I alluded to earlier.

00:50:22.840 --> 00:50:25.370
When we focus on individual domains

00:50:25.370 --> 00:50:28.690
of human life and human practice,

00:50:28.690 --> 00:50:33.530
it's completely possible
for all of them internally

00:50:33.530 --> 00:50:35.723
to make progress.

00:50:36.730 --> 00:50:41.010
And yet for them not to contribute overall

00:50:41.010 --> 00:50:43.300
to human well being

00:50:44.280 --> 00:50:48.313
because of interaction
effects between them.

00:50:50.159 --> 00:50:53.190
And that suggests that

00:50:53.190 --> 00:50:56.290
if you are interested and thinking about

00:50:56.290 --> 00:50:58.730
not simply being a pessimist,

00:50:58.730 --> 00:51:00.600
human progress is impossible,

00:51:00.600 --> 00:51:03.960
but actually trying to
build on those cases

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:06.470
in which both strong and weak progress

00:51:06.470 --> 00:51:08.440
have happened in human history.

00:51:08.440 --> 00:51:10.200
And as Dewey wanted,

00:51:10.200 --> 00:51:13.720
make them more systematic and sure-footed,

00:51:13.720 --> 00:51:17.900
then you'd better attend
to this kind of phenomenon.

00:51:17.900 --> 00:51:20.770
And for that, you need an account

00:51:20.770 --> 00:51:24.970
of how various kinds of institutions

00:51:24.970 --> 00:51:28.320
and areas of human life fit together.

00:51:28.320 --> 00:51:30.230
So I want to conclude

00:51:30.230 --> 00:51:34.370
with a confession of a
pragmatist meta philosophy,

00:51:34.370 --> 00:51:36.933
this is drawn very largely from Dewey.

00:51:38.200 --> 00:51:39.960
And it's this.

00:51:39.960 --> 00:51:42.250
Wilfrid Sellars famously says

00:51:42.250 --> 00:51:44.040
that the point of philosophy,

00:51:44.040 --> 00:51:46.300
what philosophy aims to understand

00:51:46.300 --> 00:51:49.420
is how things in the
largest sense of the term

00:51:49.420 --> 00:51:51.930
hang together in the
largest sense of the term.

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:53.573
And that seems to me, right.

00:51:54.630 --> 00:51:56.570
And it's important,

00:51:56.570 --> 00:51:59.920
because in each age,

00:51:59.920 --> 00:52:04.320
philosophy should be in the
business of trying to understand

00:52:04.320 --> 00:52:07.900
how in that age, the
conceptions and the practices

00:52:07.900 --> 00:52:10.040
that the age has inherited,

00:52:10.040 --> 00:52:12.593
fit together and hang together.

00:52:13.490 --> 00:52:15.310
And without that,

00:52:15.310 --> 00:52:20.280
without that kind of systematic
attempt to understand

00:52:21.780 --> 00:52:25.690
what the various parts and enterprises

00:52:25.690 --> 00:52:27.650
in which people engage,

00:52:27.650 --> 00:52:31.100
do in combination with one another,

00:52:31.100 --> 00:52:33.700
we can't hope to do what Dewey hoped,

00:52:33.700 --> 00:52:37.160
which was to make human
progress more systematic

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:39.490
and sure-footed than it is.

00:52:39.490 --> 00:52:43.980
This is just the tiniest beginning

00:52:43.980 --> 00:52:47.070
of an attempt to work out a version

00:52:47.070 --> 00:52:50.540
of that kind of Deweyan pragmatism

00:52:50.540 --> 00:52:52.770
by focusing on a phenomenon

00:52:52.770 --> 00:52:55.090
that I think is not well understood,

00:52:55.090 --> 00:52:58.060
and to which I hope to have
brought a little bit of clarity.

00:52:58.060 --> 00:52:59.480
Thank you.

