I think it may have been
a mistake to talk about

00:57:45.220 --> 00:57:48.110
the ideal of well-ordered
science in that context.

00:57:48.110 --> 00:57:50.170
What I wanted to do

00:57:50.170 --> 00:57:52.900
was to give some kind of substance

00:57:52.900 --> 00:57:57.670
to the idea of science
contributing to the common good.

00:57:57.670 --> 00:57:59.670
And my way of doing that

00:57:59.670 --> 00:58:02.610
is to envisage what would be,

00:58:02.610 --> 00:58:06.060
this goes back to my
sort of pragmatist views

00:58:06.060 --> 00:58:08.163
about ethics and ethical method.

00:58:09.604 --> 00:58:12.950
That goes back to the
idea that that emerges

00:58:12.950 --> 00:58:15.410
from a certain kind of
engagement with others,

00:58:15.410 --> 00:58:18.200
where we take one another's needs

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:21.180
and wishes and aspiration seriously,

00:58:21.180 --> 00:58:24.570
and seek, using the best
information we have,

00:58:24.570 --> 00:58:27.130
an outcome that all of us can live with.

00:58:27.130 --> 00:58:31.170
Now, that as an ideal

00:58:31.170 --> 00:58:33.379
is not intended to be

00:58:33.379 --> 00:58:37.880
a specification of a final
state we could reach.

00:58:37.880 --> 00:58:42.350
That as an ideal functions
as a diagnostic tool

00:58:42.350 --> 00:58:45.640
for trying to identify in the present,

00:58:45.640 --> 00:58:48.000
the places that are problematic.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:50.620
And so what I would want to do

00:58:50.620 --> 00:58:53.010
is suggest that

00:58:53.010 --> 00:58:58.010
we make progress of a certain kind,

00:58:58.400 --> 00:59:01.810
which is in a gender setting, say,

00:59:01.810 --> 00:59:05.690
by making those kinds of decisions better,

00:59:05.690 --> 00:59:09.040
so that we come to do
better at figuring out

00:59:11.750 --> 00:59:12.583
what kinds of subjects and questions

00:59:15.160 --> 00:59:17.970
would be pursued in a situation

00:59:17.970 --> 00:59:21.580
where people were more
attuned to one another

00:59:21.580 --> 00:59:25.340
and more willing to
deliberate in this way.

00:59:25.340 --> 00:59:28.340
And that we then use that

00:59:28.340 --> 00:59:31.540
as a measure of how to assess

00:59:32.540 --> 00:59:34.860
scientific progress more generally.

00:59:34.860 --> 00:59:37.770
And I'm being quite
liberal in most of the talk

00:59:37.770 --> 00:59:39.648
about the standard,

00:59:39.648 --> 00:59:41.940
I'm taking it for granted.

00:59:41.940 --> 00:59:46.850
I mean, even if the
molecular biologists of today

00:59:46.850 --> 00:59:50.690
are not doing the best
they could possibly do

00:59:50.690 --> 00:59:53.250
at figuring out what the question,

00:59:53.250 --> 00:59:55.133
they're doing pretty well, right?

00:59:56.617 --> 00:59:58.930
And I'm gonna cut them some slack on that.

00:59:58.930 --> 01:00:02.460
I mean, I think that actual
scientific communities

01:00:02.460 --> 01:00:04.790
most of the time,

01:00:04.790 --> 01:00:08.090
are asking the right kinds of questions.

01:00:08.090 --> 01:00:12.160
And that if we've moved in the direction

01:00:12.160 --> 01:00:16.320
of having the kinds of scrutinies

01:00:16.320 --> 01:00:18.920
and deliberations around
what kinds of topics

01:00:18.920 --> 01:00:20.123
are best to pursue,

01:00:21.130 --> 01:00:25.743
that the public would
rightly endorse them.

01:00:27.108 --> 01:00:28.960
So what I'm suggesting is,

01:00:28.960 --> 01:00:31.010
yeah, pretty much everything is fine,

01:00:31.010 --> 01:00:32.937
but there are going to
be these anomalous cases,

01:00:32.937 --> 01:00:35.850
and the anomalous cases show up

01:00:35.850 --> 01:00:38.920
when we start thinking
about the common good

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:41.453
in the terms that I've attempted to.

01:00:43.100 --> 01:00:45.613
So I mean, there's a
sense in which there's,

01:00:46.790 --> 01:00:50.180
there's something a little
bit vertiginous about this,

01:00:50.180 --> 01:00:53.900
because the standard that
is used as it were to assess

01:00:54.890 --> 01:00:56.900
the contribution to the common good,

01:00:56.900 --> 01:01:01.900
is a standard itself that we
can only apply imperfectly

01:01:02.010 --> 01:01:05.773
and with respect to which we
also need to make progress.

01:01:06.720 --> 01:01:08.293
More about this tomorrow.

01:01:11.880 --> 01:01:13.440
- [Audience Member] So
I wanted to ask about

01:01:13.440 --> 01:01:14.520
textbooks a little bit,

01:01:14.520 --> 01:01:17.100
because this is one place
where the disanalogy

01:01:17.100 --> 01:01:18.603
seems to come out.

01:01:19.610 --> 01:01:21.780
So in physics,

01:01:21.780 --> 01:01:25.620
a textbook might explain
an idea in a way that

01:01:25.620 --> 01:01:27.760
everyone thinks is more perspicuous

01:01:27.760 --> 01:01:30.380
than the original presentation by Einstein

01:01:30.380 --> 01:01:32.500
or whoever, the original.

01:01:32.500 --> 01:01:33.990
Usually, there's some rough edges,

01:01:33.990 --> 01:01:36.520
there's some conceptual
missteps and things,

01:01:36.520 --> 01:01:38.150
these get cleaned up.

01:01:38.150 --> 01:01:40.530
And the textbook gives you the idea,

01:01:40.530 --> 01:01:43.130
the same idea, but better.

01:01:43.130 --> 01:01:46.520
But that's very different
from what happens in music.

01:01:46.520 --> 01:01:49.220
So a music professor or
a music textbook doesn't

01:01:50.180 --> 01:01:54.110
rewrite a Beethoven quartet better,

01:01:54.110 --> 01:01:56.820
so that everything essential

01:01:56.820 --> 01:01:59.740
that you were supposed to get
out of the Beethoven quartet,

01:01:59.740 --> 01:02:02.540
you now get in a more perspicuous,

01:02:02.540 --> 01:02:04.473
better, more effective form.

01:02:05.710 --> 01:02:06.960
Instead, they just tell you

01:02:06.960 --> 01:02:08.672
to listen to the Beethoven quartet.

01:02:08.672 --> 01:02:09.505
- Exactly.

01:02:09.505 --> 01:02:10.723
- [Audience Member] So why,

01:02:10.723 --> 01:02:14.310
I guess I didn't quite see
what your take is on that,

01:02:14.310 --> 01:02:15.143
in the end.

01:02:16.590 --> 01:02:20.267
- It leads into something about which I'm,

01:02:25.050 --> 01:02:26.413
with which I'm struggling,

01:02:27.886 --> 01:02:29.950
and that is the...

01:02:31.272 --> 01:02:33.450
So I'll say another Deweyan thing.

01:02:33.450 --> 01:02:35.570
Dewey says, at one point,

01:02:35.570 --> 01:02:39.910
that any general philosophical
account of something

01:02:39.910 --> 01:02:44.150
is tested in the crucible of
its consequences for education.

01:02:44.150 --> 01:02:48.210
And so you've thrust me into
the consequences for education.

01:02:48.210 --> 01:02:50.900
Now, in the case

01:02:50.900 --> 01:02:53.810
of the sciences,

01:02:53.810 --> 01:02:56.460
if we are really interested in

01:02:56.460 --> 01:02:59.270
improving understanding,

01:02:59.270 --> 01:03:02.790
improving the, as it were,
the transformative effects

01:03:02.790 --> 01:03:06.530
that the sciences can potentially give

01:03:06.530 --> 01:03:08.620
in people's psychological lives,

01:03:08.620 --> 01:03:11.400
what we want is just what you described.

01:03:11.400 --> 01:03:15.640
Efficient, perspicuous ways of identifying

01:03:16.630 --> 01:03:19.060
what's really essential.

01:03:19.060 --> 01:03:20.950
In the case of artworks,

01:03:20.950 --> 01:03:24.070
what we want is making those artworks

01:03:24.070 --> 01:03:26.670
accessible to individuals.

01:03:26.670 --> 01:03:30.080
And it seems to be a
consequence of my views,

01:03:30.080 --> 01:03:32.120
it's a consequence I accept,

01:03:32.120 --> 01:03:35.520
that education in the arts

01:03:35.520 --> 01:03:39.320
has to be as more complicated,

01:03:39.320 --> 01:03:42.750
and more difficult than
education in the sciences.

01:03:42.750 --> 01:03:44.020
And that's because

01:03:45.640 --> 01:03:49.380
in the evolution of our
social environments,

01:03:49.380 --> 01:03:53.330
genres proliferate, styles proliferate,

01:03:53.330 --> 01:03:56.640
and if you're thinking
about a young person,

01:03:56.640 --> 01:03:58.350
for whom, you know, there's this

01:03:58.350 --> 01:04:00.763
massive collection of resources,

01:04:01.620 --> 01:04:05.340
how can that person be led to find

01:04:05.340 --> 01:04:08.240
the things that are going to

01:04:08.240 --> 01:04:11.023
have the transformative
effect on him or her.

01:04:11.920 --> 01:04:13.990
That suggests that we
actually need to spend

01:04:13.990 --> 01:04:15.830
an enormous amount of time

01:04:15.830 --> 01:04:17.360
and think very, very seriously

01:04:17.360 --> 01:04:20.820
about how we do education in the arts,

01:04:20.820 --> 01:04:23.000
whereas education in the sciences

01:04:26.300 --> 01:04:28.090
poses another challenge to us.

01:04:28.090 --> 01:04:29.010
I mean, if you're really,

01:04:29.010 --> 01:04:32.750
if you take the transformative
view that I have,

01:04:32.750 --> 01:04:35.890
then the emphasis on
education in the sciences

01:04:35.890 --> 01:04:38.360
should be precisely at getting

01:04:38.360 --> 01:04:40.390
this kind of conceptual clarity

01:04:40.390 --> 01:04:43.040
with respect to the
fundamental breakthroughs

01:04:43.040 --> 01:04:46.200
and the big ideas in the sciences,

01:04:46.200 --> 01:04:49.320
and also the understanding of
the methods of the sciences.

01:04:49.320 --> 01:04:51.760
And it should be much less

01:04:51.760 --> 01:04:54.760
on learning lists of amino acids

01:04:54.760 --> 01:04:57.170
or memorizing diagrams about

01:04:57.170 --> 01:04:59.230
complicated relations within the cell,

01:04:59.230 --> 01:05:01.290
and all of that sort of thing.

01:05:01.290 --> 01:05:03.140
And I think, at the moment,

01:05:03.140 --> 01:05:05.567
both forms of education

01:05:05.567 --> 01:05:09.140
in the affluent countries

01:05:09.140 --> 01:05:13.260
suffer from the fact that we think,

01:05:13.260 --> 01:05:15.420
in the scientific case,

01:05:15.420 --> 01:05:17.280
that we should, as it were,

01:05:17.280 --> 01:05:20.020
force everybody through this pathway,

01:05:20.020 --> 01:05:22.220
which is necessary for those

01:05:22.220 --> 01:05:23.730
who are going to want to do

01:05:23.730 --> 01:05:27.130
creative work in the sciences to traverse.

01:05:27.130 --> 01:05:30.090
And what that has done to
very many young people,

01:05:30.090 --> 01:05:32.860
I think, is deaden the
scientific curiosity

01:05:32.860 --> 01:05:34.820
with which they start.

01:05:34.820 --> 01:05:37.800
And so I don't know how to do this,

01:05:37.800 --> 01:05:40.580
or I don't know how to
formulate this recommendation,

01:05:40.580 --> 01:05:43.310
but it seems to me important
that up to a certain age,

01:05:43.310 --> 01:05:45.800
we should treat all people as if

01:05:45.800 --> 01:05:48.610
they were potentially
wanting to become scientists.

01:05:48.610 --> 01:05:50.110
But then there comes a moment

01:05:50.110 --> 01:05:52.460
at which what we want to do is imbue this

01:05:52.460 --> 01:05:54.270
sort of tremendous sense of,

01:05:54.270 --> 01:05:56.780
we wanna retain and imbue

01:05:56.780 --> 01:06:00.500
this tremendous sense of natural
curiosity about the world,

01:06:00.500 --> 01:06:03.410
with the conceptual framework

01:06:03.410 --> 01:06:06.333
that will enable the people then to,

01:06:07.220 --> 01:06:09.310
you know, to continue to engage

01:06:09.310 --> 01:06:10.760
with the scientific discoveries

01:06:10.760 --> 01:06:12.320
that will occur in their lifetimes.

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:14.820
In the case of arts, it's different,

01:06:14.820 --> 01:06:16.130
that people will come in,

01:06:16.130 --> 01:06:18.770
they will differ in the
kinds of art forms they like,

01:06:18.770 --> 01:06:21.040
they will differ in the
kinds of genres they like,

01:06:21.040 --> 01:06:23.710
they will differ in the
kinds of styles they like.

01:06:23.710 --> 01:06:26.770
And individual attention
seems to be needed

01:06:26.770 --> 01:06:29.520
both to take them to the initial things

01:06:29.520 --> 01:06:32.460
that are valuable for them,

01:06:32.460 --> 01:06:33.980
to give them a sense of what it is

01:06:33.980 --> 01:06:36.940
to have that kind of
transformative engagement with art,

01:06:36.940 --> 01:06:40.090
and then to try to broaden
from that to build.

01:06:40.090 --> 01:06:42.410
And these tasks, I think,

01:06:42.410 --> 01:06:44.950
are practically enormously difficult.

01:06:44.950 --> 01:06:46.470
And it's a consequence of my view

01:06:46.470 --> 01:06:48.070
that they have to be undertaken.

01:06:49.212 --> 01:06:50.060
So I take your point

01:06:50.060 --> 01:06:52.810
as a completely correct observation about,

01:06:52.810 --> 01:06:56.420
but it's an observation about, in the end,

01:06:56.420 --> 01:07:01.223
about the different needs
of education in these areas.

01:07:10.810 --> 01:07:11.970
- [Audience Member] When
you were talking about

01:07:11.970 --> 01:07:13.520
gains and losses,

01:07:13.520 --> 01:07:17.090
I had an association, or I
started a train of thought

01:07:17.090 --> 01:07:19.950
that was not really in
what you were saying.

01:07:19.950 --> 01:07:21.620
But I started thinking about

01:07:21.620 --> 01:07:24.040
the kinds of dynamic of gains and losses

01:07:24.040 --> 01:07:26.550
that happen in any conversation.

01:07:26.550 --> 01:07:29.360
Something said at the
beginning of the conversation,

01:07:29.360 --> 01:07:31.050
appropriate to the beginning,

01:07:31.050 --> 01:07:33.760
maybe later on in the conversation with,

01:07:33.760 --> 01:07:35.910
it's been superseded
by other insights that

01:07:36.937 --> 01:07:39.330
we've gathered or we've produced.

01:07:39.330 --> 01:07:41.270
And then I started thinking,

01:07:41.270 --> 01:07:43.100
well in the life of a
marriage, think of all the,

01:07:43.100 --> 01:07:45.300
how every time you say
something to your partner,

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:47.750
it resonates with things you would have,

01:07:47.750 --> 01:07:48.640
the way you would have said that

01:07:48.640 --> 01:07:50.130
at an earlier stage in the relationship,

01:07:50.130 --> 01:07:51.670
or the reasons why you
say it this way now,

01:07:51.670 --> 01:07:53.990
and you're using a turn of
phrase that she used before,

01:07:53.990 --> 01:07:55.170
and you're using it now and knowing

01:07:55.170 --> 01:07:57.083
that she'll know that you used it.

01:07:57.083 --> 01:08:00.400
There's this history,

01:08:00.400 --> 01:08:04.100
this thick history that
informs the present,

01:08:04.100 --> 01:08:06.040
and describes a kind of progress,

01:08:06.040 --> 01:08:08.070
or a kind of ongoing

01:08:09.617 --> 01:08:12.630
life of the party, life of the culture,

01:08:12.630 --> 01:08:14.680
because you can scale this up.

01:08:14.680 --> 01:08:18.700
And I was wondering if in a
way your idea about art was,

01:08:18.700 --> 01:08:21.100
if that was kind of the
picture you were suggesting,

01:08:21.100 --> 01:08:24.900
that the kind of transformations,

01:08:24.900 --> 01:08:28.000
the kinds of episodes,

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:30.640
that the work of art takes part of,

01:08:30.640 --> 01:08:32.800
the kinds of transformations
that affords you

01:08:32.800 --> 01:08:34.870
are like that, they're
embedded in this conversation.

01:08:34.870 --> 01:08:37.360
And this is related to the
educational point of view,

01:08:37.360 --> 01:08:38.773
because in some sense,

01:08:39.900 --> 01:08:41.990
the kind of conversation we do in the lab

01:08:41.990 --> 01:08:44.240
is different than we do in the culture.

01:08:44.240 --> 01:08:46.900
And one of the things,
imagine our students,

01:08:46.900 --> 01:08:49.330
they're coming late to the party.

01:08:49.330 --> 01:08:51.130
And there's a lot of talk
that's been going on,

01:08:51.130 --> 01:08:53.410
many bottles of wine have been drunk.

01:08:53.410 --> 01:08:55.700
And we want to sort of
get them to figure out

01:08:55.700 --> 01:08:57.730
how to listen to what's going on now,

01:08:57.730 --> 01:09:00.270
which is a function of
what's been going on.

01:09:00.270 --> 01:09:02.270
And that happens very
differently in the context of art

01:09:02.270 --> 01:09:03.360
than in the context of science.

01:09:03.360 --> 01:09:04.653
- I think that's right.

01:09:06.140 --> 01:09:09.090
I mean, one of the points I made about

01:09:09.090 --> 01:09:12.030
the Deweyan conception
of the value of art,

01:09:12.030 --> 01:09:13.000
is that

01:09:15.350 --> 01:09:20.240
the work continues to resonate with you,

01:09:20.240 --> 01:09:24.890
and its later impact on you is dependent,

01:09:24.890 --> 01:09:29.890
not only on the changes that
were produced at the time,

01:09:30.020 --> 01:09:32.400
but the way those changes have

01:09:32.400 --> 01:09:35.640
led to further interactions

01:09:35.640 --> 01:09:38.060
in your subsequent experience.

01:09:38.060 --> 01:09:40.253
And that, of course, I mean,

01:09:41.360 --> 01:09:45.770
in many cases, the process
of psychological change

01:09:45.770 --> 01:09:49.320
that goes on in relation
to a particular work of art

01:09:49.320 --> 01:09:51.453
for an individual can last a lifetime.

01:09:52.520 --> 01:09:55.710
It can be like a very
long, enduring marriage.

01:09:55.710 --> 01:09:58.420
So I mean, with respect to Joyce,

01:09:58.420 --> 01:10:01.190
I come back to Joyce
again and again and again,

01:10:01.190 --> 01:10:03.200
and it's always different.

01:10:03.200 --> 01:10:06.450
It's always, there's
always new things there.

01:10:06.450 --> 01:10:09.660
There's always something that
points me in new directions,

01:10:09.660 --> 01:10:12.480
and that's because of the
ways in which I've grown.

01:10:12.480 --> 01:10:14.400
But it's also because of the order

01:10:14.400 --> 01:10:18.360
in which a particular series of

01:10:18.360 --> 01:10:20.090
previous interactions occur.

01:10:20.090 --> 01:10:21.630
So I think that's right.

01:10:21.630 --> 01:10:24.030
I wonder whether that's entirely absent

01:10:24.030 --> 01:10:27.242
from thinking in the sciences?

01:10:27.242 --> 01:10:30.080
I'm not talking now about, you know,

01:10:30.080 --> 01:10:31.730
students coming to understand things,

01:10:31.730 --> 01:10:35.223
but I'm talking about in the
life of a creative scientist.

01:10:38.369 --> 01:10:41.250
It seems to me that there's
a lot of room for contingency

01:10:41.250 --> 01:10:44.500
built in, in both of these domains.

01:10:44.500 --> 01:10:47.630
It's not inevitable that

01:10:47.630 --> 01:10:49.750
once you start down a particular line,

01:10:49.750 --> 01:10:51.060
it has to go in this direction,

01:10:51.060 --> 01:10:54.043
it could have gone quite differently.

01:10:56.500 --> 01:10:58.500
I mean, I think that's one of the things

01:10:59.494 --> 01:11:03.540
that in retrospect is unnerving

01:11:03.540 --> 01:11:06.863
about the general phenomenon of progress.

01:11:06.863 --> 01:11:11.360
That is when we look back on
many episodes in the past,

01:11:11.360 --> 01:11:15.680
that we count, and perhaps
with very good reason,

01:11:15.680 --> 01:11:20.280
as being episodes of progress,

01:11:20.280 --> 01:11:22.350
we realized how easily
they could have gone

01:11:22.350 --> 01:11:23.720
in different directions.

01:11:23.720 --> 01:11:25.763
So contingency is unnerving, I agree.

01:11:27.660 --> 01:11:28.920
- I wonder if \I could follow up

01:11:28.920 --> 01:11:30.303
on Dewey for a moment.

01:11:34.260 --> 01:11:38.110
The first sentence of art as experience

01:11:38.110 --> 01:11:40.140
is one of the great
sentences in aesthetics,

01:11:40.140 --> 01:11:41.423
it's something like,

01:11:42.470 --> 01:11:43.710
the thing that gets in the way of

01:11:43.710 --> 01:11:46.210
framing inadequate theory of art,

01:11:46.210 --> 01:11:48.610
is the existence of the
art objects themselves,

01:11:48.610 --> 01:11:50.920
on whose basis we frame such a theory.

01:11:50.920 --> 01:11:53.200
And his ideas that we think the art

01:11:53.200 --> 01:11:55.470
is somehow intrinsic to
the object or the thing,

01:11:55.470 --> 01:11:57.240
when in fact, the thesis of the book

01:11:57.240 --> 01:11:58.950
is that art is experience.

01:11:58.950 --> 01:12:01.190
Art literally is experience.

01:12:01.190 --> 01:12:04.280
He then goes on, and offers
a theory of experience,

01:12:04.280 --> 01:12:07.010
according to which all
experiences are aesthetic.

01:12:07.010 --> 01:12:09.550
Because for him, aesthetic is,

01:12:09.550 --> 01:12:12.050
it's a condition on being an experience,

01:12:12.050 --> 01:12:13.570
that it has a certain kind of integration,

01:12:13.570 --> 01:12:15.390
a balancing of parts.

01:12:15.390 --> 01:12:16.223
So that--

01:12:16.223 --> 01:12:17.950
- So I'm gonna read
Dewey a bit differently,

01:12:17.950 --> 01:12:21.400
because it seems to me that
the dominant in the book

01:12:21.400 --> 01:12:23.480
is a tone of regret,

01:12:23.480 --> 01:12:28.410
that precisely because of the
divorce between everyday life

01:12:28.410 --> 01:12:31.603
and the art world, the
world of art objects,

01:12:32.870 --> 01:12:35.520
experience has become
flattened for people.

01:12:35.520 --> 01:12:40.520
So Dewey wants desperately
to restore the creative part,

01:12:40.950 --> 01:12:44.505
the idea not just of the
individual as a consumer

01:12:44.505 --> 01:12:47.363
of artworks which are produced elsewhere,

01:12:50.410 --> 01:12:51.490
but the, as it were,

01:12:51.490 --> 01:12:53.740
the interaction with
other people's artworks

01:12:53.740 --> 01:12:55.700
as being an interaction with

01:12:55.700 --> 01:12:58.800
one's production of things oneself.

01:12:58.800 --> 01:13:01.380
And that makes the answer
to this earlier question

01:13:01.380 --> 01:13:03.640
about education even more complicated,

01:13:03.640 --> 01:13:07.740
because it suggests that
a part of the development

01:13:07.740 --> 01:13:11.296
of the young person who comes

01:13:11.296 --> 01:13:14.880
to interact fruitfully with works of art

01:13:14.880 --> 01:13:18.750
consists in bringing about the conditions

01:13:18.750 --> 01:13:20.990
where that person can find his or her own

01:13:20.990 --> 01:13:22.820
creative work of art.

01:13:22.820 --> 01:13:25.220
So I mean, I think,

01:13:25.220 --> 01:13:27.470
yeah, I know that Dewey is inclined

01:13:27.470 --> 01:13:29.150
to sort of go off the end

01:13:29.150 --> 01:13:31.250
and say all experience is aesthetic,

01:13:31.250 --> 01:13:34.780
but that really is quite at odds with the,

01:13:34.780 --> 01:13:38.083
I think this very important
theme in art as experience.

01:13:52.266 --> 01:13:54.250
- [Audience Member] Thank you.

01:13:54.250 --> 01:13:56.920
Yeah, so I was wondering how your account

01:13:56.920 --> 01:14:00.360
would treat two different sorts of

01:14:00.360 --> 01:14:04.060
periods in the development of science.

01:14:04.060 --> 01:14:08.003
So like, the first being one, in which,

01:14:09.810 --> 01:14:12.180
as the discoveries are being made,

01:14:12.180 --> 01:14:15.330
it seems that the common
good is being benefited.

01:14:15.330 --> 01:14:17.680
Like say, if we take for granted that

01:14:17.680 --> 01:14:21.360
the development of technology
in the 20th century

01:14:22.417 --> 01:14:24.230
greatly benefited the
people who lived through it

01:14:24.230 --> 01:14:27.793
but accelerated climate change.

01:14:28.725 --> 01:14:31.430
So, you know, a period that then runs into

01:14:31.430 --> 01:14:35.510
those sorts of future
worsenings of the common good,

01:14:35.510 --> 01:14:37.360
and then kind of the flip side of that,

01:14:37.360 --> 01:14:40.420
periods in which maybe
we're not asking questions

01:14:40.420 --> 01:14:43.480
that seem like they would be fruitful,

01:14:43.480 --> 01:14:46.550
we're not making
discoveries that are helping

01:14:46.550 --> 01:14:49.530
the common good of our contemporaries,

01:14:49.530 --> 01:14:53.250
but eventually, it becomes
clear in retrospect

01:14:53.250 --> 01:14:57.260
that we were laying the
foundations for necessary,

01:14:57.260 --> 01:14:59.310
or sorry, we're laying
necessary foundations

01:14:59.310 --> 01:15:01.780
for discoveries that would help people.

01:15:01.780 --> 01:15:04.440
And I guess a slight sub
question to that second part,

01:15:04.440 --> 01:15:06.910
sorry, this is getting really long,

01:15:06.910 --> 01:15:09.350
is because that often
does happen in science,

01:15:09.350 --> 01:15:12.060
where we'd start out by asking questions

01:15:12.060 --> 01:15:15.640
that lead us to results that
are completely unpredictable,

01:15:15.640 --> 01:15:16.770
take us in different directions

01:15:16.770 --> 01:15:20.470
and could end up
benefiting the common good.

01:15:20.470 --> 01:15:23.640
I'm curious what bearing that might have

01:15:23.640 --> 01:15:26.920
on your prescription for trying to model

01:15:26.920 --> 01:15:29.570
asking the right questions, like ones that

01:15:29.570 --> 01:15:32.340
would be democratically
chosen, more or less.

01:15:32.340 --> 01:15:33.173
Thank you.

01:15:33.173 --> 01:15:34.950
- Excellent questions.

01:15:34.950 --> 01:15:36.070
There are two questions,

01:15:36.070 --> 01:15:38.720
one is about what what happens when

01:15:38.720 --> 01:15:41.853
we've got these unforeseen,
ghastly consequences?

01:15:43.091 --> 01:15:44.760
And the answer there is, you know,

01:15:44.760 --> 01:15:49.270
it's perfectly justifiable
for people at the early stages

01:15:49.270 --> 01:15:50.760
to think they're making progress,

01:15:50.760 --> 01:15:53.540
and maybe they are making
progress for a while.

01:15:53.540 --> 01:15:57.090
But it's not part of my thesis

01:15:57.090 --> 01:16:00.970
to suppose that if you go
on doing the same thing

01:16:00.970 --> 01:16:04.500
that is genuinely progressive earlier,

01:16:04.500 --> 01:16:07.630
there can't come a point at which it tips

01:16:07.630 --> 01:16:08.990
and goes the other way.

01:16:08.990 --> 01:16:11.750
So with respect to quite a
lot of environmental issues,

01:16:11.750 --> 01:16:13.490
actually, one could say,

01:16:13.490 --> 01:16:16.330
so people engage initially in something

01:16:16.330 --> 01:16:18.110
that's genuinely progressive,

01:16:18.110 --> 01:16:20.440
they keep doing it,

01:16:20.440 --> 01:16:23.610
and it keeps being
progressive for a while,

01:16:23.610 --> 01:16:24.900
but then there comes a moment

01:16:24.900 --> 01:16:29.010
at which they think of
themselves as making progress,

01:16:29.010 --> 01:16:30.900
but then they're wrong, okay.

01:16:30.900 --> 01:16:32.650
So that's the way in which

01:16:32.650 --> 01:16:34.100
I want to address that kind of case.

01:16:34.100 --> 01:16:37.620
The other case is also I think,

01:16:37.620 --> 01:16:39.800
very challenging and very interesting.

01:16:39.800 --> 01:16:43.140
So it is surely the case

01:16:43.140 --> 01:16:45.770
that there are going to be occasions

01:16:45.770 --> 01:16:49.780
on which you get unpredictable

01:16:49.780 --> 01:16:53.140
in advance benefits from pursuing

01:16:53.140 --> 01:16:56.000
a particular line of investigation.

01:16:56.000 --> 01:16:59.310
So let's now put this in the framework

01:17:01.490 --> 01:17:04.080
of people deliberating about, as it were,

01:17:04.080 --> 01:17:07.660
what projects to fund or
what projects to pursue.

01:17:07.660 --> 01:17:10.180
So the flat footed way
of doing this is to say,

01:17:10.180 --> 01:17:12.160
well, you go to the
things that are obviously

01:17:12.160 --> 01:17:16.113
going to meet the needs of
the people here and now.

01:17:17.250 --> 01:17:19.830
But I want my deliberators
to know some things

01:17:19.830 --> 01:17:21.477
about the history of science too,

01:17:21.477 --> 01:17:23.930
and one of the things I want them to know

01:17:23.930 --> 01:17:26.360
is that in the course of
the history of science,

01:17:26.360 --> 01:17:29.010
sometimes the indirect route
has been very important,

01:17:30.189 --> 01:17:33.400
and that sometimes it's
been very good just to let

01:17:33.400 --> 01:17:37.583
people who have apparently
irrelevant questions to ask,

01:17:38.930 --> 01:17:40.740
follow their hunches.

01:17:40.740 --> 01:17:45.200
So I used to always tell my students

01:17:45.200 --> 01:17:48.480
in philosophy of biology that
there were two strategies

01:17:48.480 --> 01:17:51.900
in the early decades of the 20th century

01:17:51.900 --> 01:17:56.900
for coping with human disease.

01:17:57.310 --> 01:18:00.900
One is, let's go do the
genetics of human disease

01:18:00.900 --> 01:18:04.580
right now using Mendel's methods, okay?

01:18:04.580 --> 01:18:09.500
And the other was, let's
think about fruit flies,

01:18:09.500 --> 01:18:11.320
and milk bottles and bananas

01:18:11.320 --> 01:18:14.763
and a tiny little room
in a Columbia building.

01:18:15.667 --> 01:18:18.390
That's another thing I
tell my students, you know,

01:18:19.657 --> 01:18:22.310
when Sturtevant was a sophomore,

01:18:22.310 --> 01:18:24.250
he discovered gene mapping, you know,

01:18:24.250 --> 01:18:26.823
you might consider doing
something like that, too.

01:18:28.290 --> 01:18:29.123
But,

01:18:30.580 --> 01:18:32.947
okay, so there are these
apparently irrelevant questions,

01:18:32.947 --> 01:18:37.360
and of course, they lead
back 70 or 80 years later,

01:18:37.360 --> 01:18:40.600
to exactly what the other
school wanted to do.

01:18:40.600 --> 01:18:42.490
So there are lessons that we can draw

01:18:42.490 --> 01:18:44.200
from the history of science.

01:18:44.200 --> 01:18:46.370
If you actually think of this

01:18:46.370 --> 01:18:50.820
as a process in which, you know,

01:18:50.820 --> 01:18:52.850
you do the best you can.

01:18:52.850 --> 01:18:54.760
And part of doing the best you can

01:18:54.760 --> 01:18:58.230
is to take on some ventures

01:18:58.230 --> 01:19:00.680
whose relevance isn't immediate.

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:03.083
Now, of course, you can
always choose wrongly.

01:19:04.230 --> 01:19:06.520
You can always back the wrong people

01:19:06.520 --> 01:19:09.470
who look terribly bright
and excited about some idea,

01:19:09.470 --> 01:19:11.320
and it may lead nowhere.

01:19:11.320 --> 01:19:14.910
But it seems to me that
if you were thinking

01:19:14.910 --> 01:19:17.570
about directions in
which science could go,

01:19:17.570 --> 01:19:18.940
how could you do better than this?

01:19:18.940 --> 01:19:21.570
How could you do better
than attend to human needs,

01:19:21.570 --> 01:19:23.070
in the light of all the evidence,

01:19:23.070 --> 01:19:25.160
which actually includes the very phenomena

01:19:25.160 --> 01:19:26.640
that you're pointing to?

01:19:26.640 --> 01:19:27.473
I mean,

01:19:28.730 --> 01:19:32.783
I think informed democracy
here is the best we've got.

01:19:34.530 --> 01:19:35.713
But it's not perfect.

01:19:40.830 --> 01:19:43.447
- There's a question I really
want to ask you, but Hannah.

01:19:47.200 --> 01:19:48.520
- [Hannah] Oh, thank you,

01:19:48.520 --> 01:19:51.970
thanks very much for that,
it was really interesting.

01:19:51.970 --> 01:19:54.250
I wanted to go back to the distinction

01:19:54.250 --> 01:19:56.210
that you made at the beginning between,

01:19:56.210 --> 01:20:01.050
I think it was teleological
progress towards a goal,

01:20:01.050 --> 01:20:04.820
and pragmatic progress where
you're working from something.

01:20:04.820 --> 01:20:06.670
- I think I know what this
question is going to be,

01:20:06.670 --> 01:20:08.520
but ask it anyway.

01:20:08.520 --> 01:20:09.690
- [Hannah] I was gonna say,

01:20:09.690 --> 01:20:11.836
why don't you go ahead and answer it?

01:20:11.836 --> 01:20:15.486
- No no no, why don't
you ask it, and then--

01:20:15.486 --> 01:20:20.486
- [Hannah] Well I first had
a kind of question about the,

01:20:20.820 --> 01:20:22.280
how the distinction works,

01:20:22.280 --> 01:20:26.360
but also how important it is

01:20:26.360 --> 01:20:30.120
to the larger things that you
want to do in this project.

01:20:30.120 --> 01:20:33.240
And the kind of question
that's internal to it

01:20:33.240 --> 01:20:37.290
is that when I think about progress

01:20:37.290 --> 01:20:40.240
from a problematic situation,

01:20:40.240 --> 01:20:44.270
I think about the notion of a problem.

01:20:44.270 --> 01:20:46.770
And on the face of it
a problem is something

01:20:46.770 --> 01:20:50.240
that kind of impedes
you from doing something

01:20:50.240 --> 01:20:54.490
that you want to do, or aim to do.

01:20:54.490 --> 01:20:59.490
So even though I do get and like the idea

01:20:59.520 --> 01:21:02.810
about a contrast between moving from

01:21:02.810 --> 01:21:06.670
and moving to a clearly defined goal,

01:21:06.670 --> 01:21:10.470
it does seem to me that
there's something teleological

01:21:10.470 --> 01:21:13.450
built into the idea, even of the pragmatic

01:21:15.210 --> 01:21:16.770
progress.

01:21:16.770 --> 01:21:18.530
Was that the question you were expecting?

01:21:18.530 --> 01:21:19.540
- Yes.

01:21:19.540 --> 01:21:22.140
Yes, and it's a very important question.

01:21:22.140 --> 01:21:24.700
And so I'm glad to have the
opportunity to answer it.

01:21:24.700 --> 01:21:26.580
You're right, there's gotta be something

01:21:26.580 --> 01:21:28.730
which we might think of as a local goal,

01:21:28.730 --> 01:21:29.893
an end in view.

01:21:31.140 --> 01:21:33.190
Because what I want is
relief from the problem,

01:21:33.190 --> 01:21:34.703
so in that sense, I've got,

01:21:36.450 --> 01:21:39.560
but I was a little bit more
careful than I sometimes

01:21:39.560 --> 01:21:43.780
am today because I did say
a fixed long term goal.

01:21:43.780 --> 01:21:45.430
So let me give you an example

01:21:45.430 --> 01:21:49.190
that is supposed to warm you
up for seeing the difference

01:21:49.190 --> 01:21:52.200
between what we might
think of as local teleology

01:21:52.200 --> 01:21:53.073
or local,

01:21:54.886 --> 01:21:56.620
you know, local goal directedness,

01:21:56.620 --> 01:21:59.000
and what I was calling teleology,

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:01.853
in the having a fixed
long term goal sense.

01:22:03.727 --> 01:22:05.103
Okay, so I,

01:22:06.710 --> 01:22:09.610
a pretty poor gardener these days.

01:22:09.610 --> 01:22:13.650
And I look at my flower
bed, and it's dreary,

01:22:13.650 --> 01:22:15.850
and it's full of weeds,

01:22:15.850 --> 01:22:18.680
and I wanna do something about it.

01:22:18.680 --> 01:22:21.670
And I have a number of desiderata.

01:22:21.670 --> 01:22:26.360
And these desiderata may
not be jointly satisfiable,

01:22:26.360 --> 01:22:29.160
okay, that's an important
part of the story.

01:22:29.160 --> 01:22:31.943
I want lots of color,

01:22:33.030 --> 01:22:38.030
I want blooms at different
times of the summer.

01:22:39.330 --> 01:22:42.430
You know, I want a harmony of colors,

01:22:42.430 --> 01:22:44.600
I want easy care.

01:22:44.600 --> 01:22:46.760
I want it to be drought resistant,

01:22:46.760 --> 01:22:48.540
and blah blah blah blah blah.

01:22:48.540 --> 01:22:50.570
So what do I do?

01:22:50.570 --> 01:22:53.240
I start out in a particular direction,

01:22:53.240 --> 01:22:55.383
I buy some seeds,

01:22:56.558 --> 01:22:59.710
I use these ideas in

01:23:03.440 --> 01:23:05.299
sort of starting up buying some plants

01:23:05.299 --> 01:23:08.560
and putting seeds in and watering,

01:23:08.560 --> 01:23:11.920
and, you know, some years later,

01:23:11.920 --> 01:23:15.380
after numerous experiments and trials

01:23:15.380 --> 01:23:19.410
and applications of these desiderata,

01:23:19.410 --> 01:23:22.170
and others that have
cropped up in the meantime,

01:23:22.170 --> 01:23:24.560
I get something and I
say, this is pretty good,

01:23:24.560 --> 01:23:26.940
this is the sort of thing I wanted.

01:23:26.940 --> 01:23:28.410
Going back to Alver's point,

01:23:28.410 --> 01:23:29.500
it could have gone in

01:23:29.500 --> 01:23:32.423
any number of different directions, right?

01:23:33.550 --> 01:23:35.180
I wanna say that in a certain sense,

01:23:35.180 --> 01:23:37.660
that wasn't teleological, I didn't have,

01:23:37.660 --> 01:23:40.603
as it were at the beginning, a fixed goal.

01:23:44.278 --> 01:23:46.597
I had a problem in the sense

01:23:48.480 --> 01:23:51.503
of something that was unsatisfactory,

01:23:51.503 --> 01:23:53.370
it's unsatisfactoriness

01:23:53.370 --> 01:23:56.100
was associated with various desiderata,

01:23:56.100 --> 01:23:58.140
but you know, I revised

01:23:58.140 --> 01:24:00.313
some of the desiderata along the way.

01:24:01.670 --> 01:24:05.790
And it's all been a sort of contingent,

01:24:05.790 --> 01:24:08.670
path directed process.

01:24:08.670 --> 01:24:10.980
The deeper question you're asking is,

01:24:10.980 --> 01:24:13.260
how do you identify
problems, what's a problem,

01:24:13.260 --> 01:24:15.260
and that is a very deep question,

01:24:15.260 --> 01:24:17.660
but I want to say much
more about that tomorrow.

01:24:19.690 --> 01:24:22.773
That is, I mean, that's a really
deep and serious question.

01:24:23.718 --> 01:24:26.310
And anyone who wants
to talk about progress,

01:24:26.310 --> 01:24:27.420
as I want to talk about it,

01:24:27.420 --> 01:24:29.433
has to have an answer to that question.

01:24:36.140 --> 01:24:38.150
- I'd like to ask you about the relation

01:24:38.150 --> 01:24:42.730
between the conception of
progress that you're roughing out,

01:24:42.730 --> 01:24:45.140
and the conception of progress

01:24:45.140 --> 01:24:47.300
that the scientists, or the artists,

01:24:47.300 --> 01:24:49.560
the practitioners themselves,

01:24:49.560 --> 01:24:51.500
and what they're doing.

01:24:51.500 --> 01:24:52.550
I mean, if I'm an artist,

01:24:52.550 --> 01:24:55.380
and my overriding objective
is to make something

01:24:55.380 --> 01:24:58.830
truly avant garde, I don't
care about the public good.

01:24:58.830 --> 01:25:00.950
I mean, the public good
can go and get stuffed,

01:25:00.950 --> 01:25:03.973
I want to do something
that moves things on.

01:25:06.900 --> 01:25:09.280
If you think about psychiatry,

01:25:09.280 --> 01:25:11.930
psychiatrists really aren't really,

01:25:11.930 --> 01:25:14.240
what's the word I want, bothered

01:25:14.240 --> 01:25:18.670
about whether there has really
been progress in psychiatry.

01:25:18.670 --> 01:25:20.730
Now, from the point of
view of the public good,

01:25:20.730 --> 01:25:23.610
there's clearly been a lot
of progress in psychiatry.

01:25:23.610 --> 01:25:25.410
I mean, patients are no longer

01:25:25.410 --> 01:25:28.010
bundled into unfunded asylums,

01:25:28.010 --> 01:25:31.870
and standards of clinical
care are a lot better.

01:25:31.870 --> 01:25:35.160
But when psychiatrists torture about

01:25:36.080 --> 01:25:37.520
whether there's been any progress,

01:25:37.520 --> 01:25:39.310
what they mean is that for,

01:25:39.310 --> 01:25:42.040
especially for complex
disorders like schizophrenia,

01:25:42.040 --> 01:25:44.020
or major depression,

01:25:44.020 --> 01:25:46.350
they don't understand what's going on

01:25:46.350 --> 01:25:49.020
any better than they did a century ago.

01:25:49.020 --> 01:25:50.560
That's the fear,

01:25:50.560 --> 01:25:52.670
that when you're looking for
the nuts and bolts of it,

01:25:52.670 --> 01:25:55.440
and it's not really an
issue about the public good,

01:25:55.440 --> 01:25:58.540
you would not assuage that worry,

01:25:58.540 --> 01:26:00.940
maybe we're not making any
progress in psychiatry,

01:26:00.940 --> 01:26:03.050
by saying, but look the
standards of clinical care

01:26:03.050 --> 01:26:05.260
are improved out of all recognition.

01:26:05.260 --> 01:26:06.970
That's not what they mean.

01:26:06.970 --> 01:26:08.163
Or if, sorry.

01:26:09.480 --> 01:26:13.070
- Again, it's like the question
that was asked down here,

01:26:13.070 --> 01:26:16.270
it's two questions, and
they're both good ones,

01:26:16.270 --> 01:26:18.560
and they're both ones
that I need to face up to.

01:26:18.560 --> 01:26:20.890
Let me deal with the psychiatrist first.

01:26:20.890 --> 01:26:25.020
So the psychiatrists
may well be in the grip

01:26:25.020 --> 01:26:27.760
of what I call the official view, right?

01:26:27.760 --> 01:26:30.120
So they may be thinking, what we gotta do

01:26:30.120 --> 01:26:32.790
is tell the truth about the human psyche,

01:26:32.790 --> 01:26:35.373
and the way it gets
disordered in various ways.

01:26:36.330 --> 01:26:40.190
And that may blind them to
one of the modes of progress,

01:26:40.190 --> 01:26:43.760
I mean, part of my view allows,

01:26:43.760 --> 01:26:46.273
and you can see this in the way that

01:26:46.273 --> 01:26:49.380
I talked about the
contributions of science

01:26:49.380 --> 01:26:51.930
not being simply sets of propositions,

01:26:51.930 --> 01:26:54.730
but also techniques
and so on and so forth,

01:26:54.730 --> 01:26:59.010
is that you might make
progress in one mode.

01:26:59.010 --> 01:27:00.750
And even though you were making

01:27:00.750 --> 01:27:03.010
no progress whatsoever in another mode,

01:27:03.010 --> 01:27:05.430
and what I want to say
about the psychiatrist,

01:27:05.430 --> 01:27:07.990
is that they're, because they perhaps

01:27:07.990 --> 01:27:10.540
have inherited this official view

01:27:10.540 --> 01:27:13.210
in its application to psychiatry,

01:27:13.210 --> 01:27:15.760
they've overlooked an important mode

01:27:15.760 --> 01:27:17.580
of psychiatric progress,

01:27:17.580 --> 01:27:21.520
which is in forms of practical care.

01:27:21.520 --> 01:27:25.890
Okay, so that's the way
I would deal with that.

01:27:25.890 --> 01:27:27.653
So what about the artists?

01:27:29.400 --> 01:27:31.760
So the artists are also, I mean,

01:27:31.760 --> 01:27:34.640
the artist you describe is very much

01:27:36.095 --> 01:27:39.740
in an internal tradition

01:27:39.740 --> 01:27:43.180
with which that artist is interacting.

01:27:43.180 --> 01:27:44.300
It's not just, you know,

01:27:44.300 --> 01:27:46.040
I wanna do something avant garde,

01:27:46.040 --> 01:27:49.810
but rather, I've got
ideas about where to take,

01:27:49.810 --> 01:27:52.430
you know, abstract expressionism next,

01:27:52.430 --> 01:27:55.520
or I've got an idea about

01:27:55.520 --> 01:27:58.213
where to go next with 12 tone music,

01:28:00.438 --> 01:28:03.760
or what minimalism should do next.

01:28:03.760 --> 01:28:08.290
So that's very much again, you know,

01:28:08.290 --> 01:28:12.780
the idea of there being
sort of an internal

01:28:12.780 --> 01:28:16.160
sort of standard that's
cut off from the public.

01:28:16.160 --> 01:28:18.240
But there are other artists whom I think

01:28:18.240 --> 01:28:21.510
are moved by the fact that

01:28:21.510 --> 01:28:24.130
the kind of art that is being produced

01:28:24.130 --> 01:28:27.650
doesn't speak to certain
classes of people.

01:28:27.650 --> 01:28:30.262
So some artists, I think,

01:28:30.262 --> 01:28:32.220
are moved to say, look,

01:28:32.220 --> 01:28:34.980
what we need is a new form of music,

01:28:34.980 --> 01:28:36.500
because everybody's, you know,

01:28:36.500 --> 01:28:40.733
I mean, the young are not turned on by,

01:28:41.600 --> 01:28:44.042
you know, sort of the high music

01:28:44.042 --> 01:28:49.042
that has gotten such a lot
of status in the culture.

01:28:49.050 --> 01:28:51.133
What we need is crossover stuff,

01:28:52.170 --> 01:28:55.600
Radiohead, and Radiohead
needs to come to terms

01:28:55.600 --> 01:28:58.290
with Ligaty, and then
we'll put the two together

01:28:58.290 --> 01:29:00.823
and we're gonna make something fantastic.

01:29:01.740 --> 01:29:05.270
And that's much more outwardly directed,

01:29:05.270 --> 01:29:08.120
it seems to me, so it depends,

01:29:08.120 --> 01:29:10.410
and you can think of this in
terms of the novel, right?

01:29:10.410 --> 01:29:12.390
I mean, you know,

01:29:12.390 --> 01:29:16.713
the marginalized audiences to
whom my novel will now speak.

01:29:17.819 --> 01:29:20.793
And that, I think that's a genuine,

01:29:22.250 --> 01:29:23.697
there you see the social stuff coming,

01:29:23.697 --> 01:29:26.233
and so I think it's a mixture.

01:29:27.890 --> 01:29:30.710
But it's a really good
thing to think about.

01:29:30.710 --> 01:29:32.190
- I guess I have a background

01:29:32.190 --> 01:29:34.330
Quinian kind of worry about...

01:29:35.630 --> 01:29:39.030
If you said my conception of progress is

01:29:39.030 --> 01:29:42.900
picked up from what's
internal to each discipline,

01:29:42.900 --> 01:29:46.390
and what the practitioners are
thinking in each discipline,

01:29:46.390 --> 01:29:47.810
that would be one take.

01:29:47.810 --> 01:29:49.740
But as you presented it,

01:29:49.740 --> 01:29:53.030
your conception of progress
seems to come from outside

01:29:53.030 --> 01:29:54.920
any particular discipline

01:29:54.920 --> 01:29:58.480
to be something that's
being worked out a priori.

01:29:58.480 --> 01:30:00.965
- No, not a priori,

01:30:00.965 --> 01:30:05.230
but actually in terms
of a wider reflection,

01:30:05.230 --> 01:30:07.640
which I pointed to at both
the beginning and the end.

01:30:07.640 --> 01:30:09.820
I mean, the conception of progress comes,

01:30:09.820 --> 01:30:13.940
is really wrestling with skepticism

01:30:13.940 --> 01:30:16.070
about the very idea.

01:30:16.070 --> 01:30:18.960
The very idea of progress,
what is it to talk about?

01:30:18.960 --> 01:30:23.323
And that skepticism is
partly based on the idea of,

01:30:25.150 --> 01:30:28.900
yeah, you can talk about progress internal

01:30:28.900 --> 01:30:32.320
to one of these enterprises or domains.

01:30:32.320 --> 01:30:34.170
But when you enlarge the frame

01:30:34.170 --> 01:30:36.520
and you look at the human consequences,

01:30:36.520 --> 01:30:38.720
I mean, if you think
about all of the people

01:30:40.380 --> 01:30:45.380
who are saying, who are
deriding the idea of progress,

01:30:45.700 --> 01:30:47.810
they're all moved by this thought

01:30:47.810 --> 01:30:50.630
that as you expand your vision, right,

01:30:50.630 --> 01:30:53.410
so take a very simple example.

01:30:53.410 --> 01:30:57.090
We both grew up on an island

01:30:58.170 --> 01:31:01.030
that made fantastic economic progress

01:31:01.030 --> 01:31:04.070
in the 19th century, right?

01:31:04.070 --> 01:31:05.550
Expand the frame,

01:31:05.550 --> 01:31:08.800
look at the places that
were feeding into that.

01:31:08.800 --> 01:31:10.400
And you wanna say, no,

01:31:10.400 --> 01:31:12.220
it's compromised by all of that,

01:31:12.220 --> 01:31:14.540
it's compromised by the
exploitation of India

01:31:14.540 --> 01:31:15.510
and so on and so forth.

01:31:15.510 --> 01:31:18.440
And it's precisely that move,

01:31:18.440 --> 01:31:22.190
the move of expanding the frame.

01:31:22.190 --> 01:31:24.760
And so that's what pushes me,

01:31:24.760 --> 01:31:26.900
and it pushes me in the genetics case,

01:31:26.900 --> 01:31:30.450
I mean I was challenged by
the very first question.

01:31:30.450 --> 01:31:33.610
That challenges me to
look at the ways in which

01:31:35.010 --> 01:31:40.010
the consequences pan out
for the broader society.

01:31:40.830 --> 01:31:42.620
Because it seems to me,

01:31:42.620 --> 01:31:45.470
that's where you have to
respond to skepticism.

01:31:45.470 --> 01:31:47.980
So it's not a priori,

01:31:47.980 --> 01:31:51.720
but it's based not only on looking

01:31:51.720 --> 01:31:54.690
at the internal constraints
of the discipline,

01:31:54.690 --> 01:31:58.600
but also at a broader set of facts

01:31:58.600 --> 01:32:01.280
about how that discipline is situated,

01:32:01.280 --> 01:32:05.010
that then, if not attended to,

01:32:05.010 --> 01:32:08.207
foster this kind of worry and
skepticism about progress.

01:32:08.207 --> 01:32:09.612
Does that make sense?

01:32:09.612 --> 01:32:10.445
- [John] That makes perfect sense.

01:32:10.445 --> 01:32:11.278
- Okay, good.

01:32:13.100 --> 01:32:13.973
- Last call.

01:32:18.977 --> 01:32:20.365
- [Audience Member] I think
I just wanna follow up

01:32:20.365 --> 01:32:22.560
this conversation you were
just having with John,

01:32:22.560 --> 01:32:27.030
'cause it does seem like
you're tying progress,

01:32:27.030 --> 01:32:31.053
potentially too much to
its actual effects on,

01:32:32.000 --> 01:32:35.340
you know, the flourishing of
people in the broader society.

01:32:35.340 --> 01:32:36.173
I mean, it seems like there's

01:32:36.173 --> 01:32:37.930
a perfectly intelligible narrative

01:32:37.930 --> 01:32:39.610
where there's all kinds
of progress going on

01:32:39.610 --> 01:32:41.420
in the science and the arts.

01:32:41.420 --> 01:32:43.870
If you start from the
internal perspective,

01:32:43.870 --> 01:32:45.580
the problems get more and more difficult

01:32:45.580 --> 01:32:49.320
and challenging and
potentially inaccessible.

01:32:49.320 --> 01:32:51.920
And so the benefits of engaging with them

01:32:51.920 --> 01:32:54.430
become harder for the society

01:32:55.437 --> 01:32:57.020
to realize in some ways,

01:32:57.020 --> 01:33:00.130
but you might say, there's
a lot of progress going on.

01:33:00.130 --> 01:33:02.470
Unfortunately, as we've disinvested

01:33:02.470 --> 01:33:06.440
in education simultaneously
with the problems becoming,

01:33:06.440 --> 01:33:08.740
you know, more and more challenging

01:33:08.740 --> 01:33:11.140
to understand on their own terms,

01:33:11.140 --> 01:33:13.530
the benefits of this
progress are accessible

01:33:13.530 --> 01:33:16.823
to an ever smaller set of people.

01:33:18.032 --> 01:33:19.570
I want to say about that situation,

01:33:19.570 --> 01:33:21.530
it might still be the case that if people

01:33:21.530 --> 01:33:24.300
could acquire an
appreciation for the things

01:33:24.300 --> 01:33:26.210
that are going on in
the different domains,

01:33:26.210 --> 01:33:28.940
it would enrich their
lives in all kinds of ways

01:33:28.940 --> 01:33:31.750
counter factually, but it isn't, in fact,

01:33:31.750 --> 01:33:34.410
because they don't have the educational

01:33:34.410 --> 01:33:35.500
opportunities and so on,

01:33:35.500 --> 01:33:37.550
it seems like in that situation,

01:33:37.550 --> 01:33:40.330
we do have progress, but
it's not bringing about

01:33:40.330 --> 01:33:44.653
the kinds of Deweyan benefits
that you're pointing to.

01:33:45.550 --> 01:33:46.580
So what do you say about that?

01:33:46.580 --> 01:33:47.413
- I say that

01:33:50.100 --> 01:33:52.570
a fourth part of the
logic of progress concepts

01:33:52.570 --> 01:33:54.640
is that you're always looking at a frame.

01:33:54.640 --> 01:33:57.260
And you can take the internal frame,

01:33:57.260 --> 01:34:01.460
and we can say, I mean, we
do say a lot of the time,

01:34:01.460 --> 01:34:04.690
this scientific domain
is making rapid progress,

01:34:04.690 --> 01:34:06.335
and we don't even think about

01:34:06.335 --> 01:34:09.350
whether the questions
that are being answered

01:34:09.350 --> 01:34:11.610
have social merit or anything like that.

01:34:11.610 --> 01:34:13.860
So that seems to me perfectly reasonable.

01:34:13.860 --> 01:34:14.773
But when,

01:34:16.060 --> 01:34:18.760
I think the skeptics and the cynics say,

01:34:18.760 --> 01:34:21.910
enlarge the frame, see if
your judgment is stable

01:34:21.910 --> 01:34:23.680
when you enlarge the frame.

01:34:23.680 --> 01:34:26.280
And what they want from progress

01:34:26.280 --> 01:34:29.460
is something that when you
move to the widest frame,

01:34:29.460 --> 01:34:32.300
which is probably the impact on humans,

01:34:32.300 --> 01:34:34.033
and maybe more than humans,

01:34:35.040 --> 01:34:37.870
across, you know, not only the present,

01:34:37.870 --> 01:34:41.300
but also the future,
turns out to be positive.

01:34:41.300 --> 01:34:43.570
So it's as if you could

01:34:43.570 --> 01:34:45.680
imagine a sequence of frames that get

01:34:45.680 --> 01:34:48.120
wider and wider and wider.

01:34:48.120 --> 01:34:51.270
The thought is that real progress is,

01:34:51.270 --> 01:34:53.690
look at the narrowest frame, it's there,

01:34:53.690 --> 01:34:55.130
you enlarge the frame, it's there,

01:34:55.130 --> 01:34:57.933
it continues, it's stable
as you enlarge the frame.

01:34:58.820 --> 01:35:00.730
So that's the thought.

01:35:00.730 --> 01:35:03.160
Now, the example that you
gave was really interesting,

01:35:03.160 --> 01:35:06.880
because of course, you
can get this situation,

01:35:06.880 --> 01:35:09.090
and it almost came up in the question,

01:35:09.090 --> 01:35:11.250
there was another scenario
that was very close

01:35:11.250 --> 01:35:13.820
to the two that were offered at the back.

01:35:13.820 --> 01:35:17.350
Where you think about a
scientific development,

01:35:17.350 --> 01:35:20.150
like the discovery of quantum mechanics,

01:35:20.150 --> 01:35:24.260
which from the internal point
of view is really important.

01:35:24.260 --> 01:35:25.540
And then in the 30s,

01:35:25.540 --> 01:35:27.580
starts to trouble various people

01:35:27.580 --> 01:35:30.480
because it enables the production

01:35:30.480 --> 01:35:33.360
of these extraordinary weapons, okay?

01:35:33.360 --> 01:35:37.109
Now, what happens if you get

01:35:37.109 --> 01:35:40.720
an awful social consequence because

01:35:42.210 --> 01:35:45.760
a scientific, piece of
scientific understanding,

01:35:45.760 --> 01:35:48.220
answer to what seemed to
be a very good question,

01:35:48.220 --> 01:35:49.630
gets translated.

01:35:49.630 --> 01:35:51.970
So this is exactly what I'm thinking of

01:35:51.970 --> 01:35:53.910
as institutional friction,

01:35:53.910 --> 01:35:58.910
you can have an
institution of policymaking

01:35:59.210 --> 01:36:01.550
that surrounds the science

01:36:01.550 --> 01:36:03.970
and translates it into practice,

01:36:03.970 --> 01:36:05.690
that does horrible things,

01:36:05.690 --> 01:36:09.940
even though the institution
itself is not guilty.

01:36:09.940 --> 01:36:11.010
So that can happen,

01:36:11.010 --> 01:36:14.340
and that I think happens
in the case you imagine,

01:36:14.340 --> 01:36:16.139
where, as it were,

01:36:16.139 --> 01:36:19.010
the sciences are making
these wonderful benefits,

01:36:19.010 --> 01:36:21.240
but the educational system is science,

01:36:21.240 --> 01:36:23.940
science is so dismal and deteriorating,

01:36:23.940 --> 01:36:27.580
that the effect on the broader
public isn't appreciated.

01:36:27.580 --> 01:36:29.353
So, absolutely, I mean,

01:36:30.650 --> 01:36:33.020
so there's a lot to be
said here about frames

01:36:33.020 --> 01:36:36.593
and the interactions among
institutions within society.

01:36:37.730 --> 01:36:38.563
Yeah.

01:36:39.622 --> 01:36:41.722
And I hope to say all of it at some point.

01:36:42.560 --> 01:36:43.923
And better than I just did.

01:36:45.120 --> 01:36:45.953
- That was wonderful.

01:36:45.953 --> 01:36:49.666
Lucid, deep, unexpected,
thank you very much.

